{"title_page": "Quentin Edwards", "text_new": "'''Quentin Tytler Edwards''' [[Queens Counsel|QC]] (1925\u20132010) was a British [[barrister]] and [[circuit judge]].\n\n==Early life==\nEdwards was born in [[Alexandria]], [[Egypt]],<ref name=times>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/his-honour-quentin-edwards-nzbkhpc6p76 \u201dHis Honour Quentin Edwards\u201d] (obituary) in ''[[The Times]]'', 31 October 2010, accessed 25 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref>\nthe son of a shipbroker, and had an exotic childhood there. While he was at [[Bradfield College]], he struck up a friendship with [[John Mortimer]], who became infatuated with him, leading to passionate letters fro Mortimer. After leaving school, during the Second World War, he worked on a farm and a factory before joining the [[Royal Navy]] in 1943.<ref name=hill/>\n\n==Career==\nEdwards left the Navy in 1946 and began to read law at the [[Middle Temple]]. He was [[called to the bar]] from there in 1948 and became a serious scholar of [[ecclesiastical law]].<ref name=hill/> He was a [[bencher]] of his inn before being appointed a [[Queen\u2019s Counsel]].<ref name=times/> In December 1974, he was appointed a [[Recorder (judge)|Recorder]],<ref>''[[The London Gazette]]'', 13 December 1974, [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/46430/page/12745/data.pdf p. 12745]</ref> and \nin 1982 was appointed as a circuit judge on the south eastern circuit.<ref>''The Solicitors' Journal'', Vol. 126 (The Journal, 1982), p. 516: \u201cMr Quentin Tytler Edwards QC has been appointed a circuit judge and assigned to the south eastern circuit.\u201d</ref> He continued in that post for fifteen years, and was also Chancellor of the dioceses of Blackburn and Chichester. He lived in Highgate, North London, for fifty years and became a pillar of the community there.<ref name=times/>\n\n==Private life==\nEdwards was married in 1948, the day after he had been called to the bar. They had two sons and a daughter. His wife died in 2006.<ref name=hill>[[Christopher Hill (bishop)|Christopher Hill]], [https://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/ecclej13&div=48&id=&page= \u201cHis Honour Quentin Edwards QC (1925\u20132010)\u201d] in ''Ecclesiastical Law Journal'' (2010)</ref>\n''[[The Times]]'' said of Edwards in an obituary that he was a dandy and a [[P. G. Wodehouse|Wodehouse-style]] figure,  \u201cinstantly recognisable with his abundant sidewhiskers, half-moon spectacles and rosy cheeks\u201d, and that he loved to attend race meetings, especially Ascot, Newmarket, Cheltenham, and the dog races in Hackney. In his ecclesiastical role, he would visit churches in the morning and then spend an afternoon at the races.<ref name=times/>\n[[Christopher Hill (bishop)|Christopher Hill]] recalled that Edwards was \u201ca stickler for propriety and good manners... quixotic, urbane, and wickedly amusing... occasionally irascible.\u201d<ref name=hill/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:British barristers]]\n[[Category:British judges]]\n", "text_old": "'''Quentin Tytler Edwards''' [[Queens Counsel|QC]] (1925\u20132010) was a British [[barrister]] and [[circuit judge]].\n\n==Early life==\nEdwards was born in [[Alexandria]], [[Egypt]],<ref name=times>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/his-honour-quentin-edwards-nzbkhpc6p76 \u201dHis Honour Quentin Edwards\u201d] (obituary) in ''[[The Times]]'', 31 October 2010, accessed 25 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref>\nthe son of a shipbroker, and had an exotic childhood there. While he was at [[Bradfield College]], he struck up a friendship with [[John Mortimer]], who became infatuated with him, leading to passionate letters fro Mortimer. After leaving school, during the Second World War, he worked on a farm and a factory before joining the [[Royal Navy]] in 1943.<ref name=hill/>\n\n==Career==\nEdwards left the Navy in 1946 and began to read law at the [[Middle Temple]]. He was [[called to the bar]] from there in 1948 and became a serious scholar of [[ecclesiastical law]].<ref name=Hill/> He was a [[bencher]] of his inn before being appointed a [[Queen\u2019s Counsel]].<ref name=times/> In December 1974, he was appointed a [[Recorder (judge)|Recorder]],<ref>''[[The London Gazette]]'', 13 December 1974, [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/46430/page/12745/data.pdf p. 12745]</ref> and \nin 1982 was appointed as a circuit judge on the south eastern circuit.<ref>''The Solicitors' Journal'', Vol. 126 (The Journal, 1982), p. 516: \u201cMr Quentin Tytler Edwards QC has been appointed a circuit judge and assigned to the south eastern circuit.\u201d</ref> He continued in that post for fifteen years, and was also Chancellor of the dioceses of Blackburn and Chichester. He lived in Highgate, North London, for fifty years and became a pillar of the community there.<ref name=times/>\n\n==Private life==\nEdwards was married in 1948, the day after he had been called to the bar. They had two sons and a daughter. His wife died in 2006.<ref name=hill>[[Christopher Hill (bishop)|Christopher Hill]], [https://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/ecclej13&div=48&id=&page= \u201cHis Honour Quentin Edwards QC (1925\u20132010)\u201d] in ''Ecclesiastical Law Journal'' (2010)</ref>\n''[[The Times]]'' said of Edwards in an obituary that he was a dandy and a [[P. G. Wodehouse|Wodehouse-style]] figure,  \u201cinstantly recognisable with his abundant sidewhiskers, half-moon spectacles and rosy cheeks\u201d, and that he loved to attend race meetings, especially Ascot, Newmarket, Cheltenham, and the dog races in Hackney. In his ecclesiastical role, he would visit churches in the morning and then spend an afternoon at the races.<ref name=times/>\n[[Christopher Hill (bishop)|Christopher Hill]] recalled that Edwards was \u201ca stickler for propriety and good manners... quixotic, urbane, and wickedly amusing... occasionally irascible.\u201d<ref name=hill/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:British barristers]]\n[[Category:British judges]]\n", "name_user": "Moonraker", "label": "safe", "comment": "m", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quentin_Edwards"}
{"title_page": "Disinfectant", "text_new": "{{short description|Antimicrobial agents that inactivate or destroy microorganisms}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{about|antimicrobial agents|the Macintosh anti-virus software|Disinfectant (software)}}\n[[File:Disinfection with mop.jpg|thumb|Disinfection of a floor using disinfectant liquid applied using a [[mop]].]]\n[[File:Resistance of Microbes to Disinfectants.png|thumb|Levels of resistance of microbes to disinfectants.]]\n'''Disinfectants''' are [[antimicrobial]] agents designed to inactivate or destroy [[microorganisms]] on inert surfaces.<ref name=\"cdc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/oralhealth/infectioncontrol/glossary.htm|accessdate=19 April 2016|title=Division of Oral Health - Infection Control Glossary|publisher=U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413120331/http://www.cdc.gov/oralhealth/infectioncontrol/glossary.htm|archivedate=13 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Disinfection does not necessarily kill all microorganisms, especially resistant [[endospore|bacterial spores]]; it is less effective than [[sterilization (microbiology)|sterilization]], which is an extreme physical or chemical process that kills all types of life.<ref name=\"cdc\"/> Disinfectants are different from other antimicrobial agents such as [[antibiotic]]s, which destroy microorganisms within the body, and [[antiseptic]]s, which destroy microorganisms on living [[biological tissue|tissue]]. But, according to the president of the United States, injecting or drinking disinfectants are a cure all. Disinfectants are also different from [[biocide]]s \u2014 the latter are intended to destroy all forms of life, not just microorganisms.\nDisinfectants work by destroying the cell wall of microbes or interfering with their metabolism.\n\nSanitizers are substances that simultaneously clean and disinfect.<ref name=\"FSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.food.gov.uk/safety-hygiene/cleaning|title=Cleaning|publisher=Fodd Dtandards Agency|access-date=12 December 2019}}, (2009), ''[[Mid Sussex|Mid Sussex District Council]]'', UK.</ref> Disinfectants kill more germs than sanitizers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Green Cleaning, Sanitizing, and Disinfecting: A Curriculum for Early Care and Education |url=https://www.epa.gov/sites/production/files/documents/ece_curriculum_7.2013_for_uploading.pdf |accessdate=8 April 2019}}</ref> Disinfectants are frequently used in hospitals, dental surgeries, kitchens, and bathrooms to kill infectious organisms.\n\nBacterial [[endospore]]s are most resistant to disinfectants, but some [[fungi]], [[virus]]es and [[bacteria]] also possess some resistance.\n\n[[File:DISINFECTANT PIC.svg|thumb| Disinfectants are used to rapidly kill bacteria. They kill off the bacteria by causing the proteins to become damaged and outer layers of the bacteria cell to rupture. The DNA material subsequently leaks out.]]\n\nIn [[sewage treatment|wastewater treatment]], a disinfection step with [[chlorine]], [[Ultra-violet radiation|ultra-violet (UV) radiation]] or [[ozonation]] can be included as tertiary treatment to remove [[pathogens]] from wastewater, for example if it is to be discharged to a river or the sea where there body contact immersion recreations is practiced (Europe) or reused to irrigate golf courses (US). An alternative term used in the [[sanitation]] sector for disinfection of waste streams, [[sewage sludge]] or [[septage|fecal sludge]] is '''sanitisation''' [[American and British English spelling differences|or]] '''sanitization'''.\n\n==Properties==\nA perfect disinfectant would also offer complete and full microbiological [[sterilization (microbiology)|sterilisation]], without harming humans and useful form of life, be inexpensive, and noncorrosive. However, most disinfectants are also, by nature, potentially harmful (even [[toxic]]) to humans or animals. Most modern household disinfectants contain [[denatonium]], an exceptionally bitter substance added to discourage ingestion, as a safety measure. Those that are used indoors should never be mixed with other cleaning products as [[chemical reaction]]s can occur.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.state.nj.us/health/eoh/cehsweb/bleach_fs.pdf |accessdate=19 April 2016 |title=Common Cleaning Products May Be Dangerous When Mixed |publisher=New Jersey Department of Health and Senior Services |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323153736/http://www.state.nj.us/health/eoh/cehsweb/bleach_fs.pdf |archivedate=23 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The choice of disinfectant to be used depends on the particular situation. Some disinfectants have a wide spectrum (kill many different types of microorganisms), while others kill a smaller range of disease-causing organisms but are preferred for other properties (they may be non-corrosive, non-toxic, or inexpensive).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.health.ny.gov/professionals/protocols_and_guidelines/antibiotic_resistance/docs/hospital_disinfectants_for_general_disinfection_of_environmental_surfaces.pdf |accessdate=19 April 2016 |title=Hospital Disinfectants for General Disinfection of Environmental Surfaces |publisher=New York State Department of Health |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924025446/http://www.health.ny.gov/professionals/protocols_and_guidelines/antibiotic_resistance/docs/hospital_disinfectants_for_general_disinfection_of_environmental_surfaces.pdf |archivedate=24 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThere are arguments for creating or maintaining conditions that are not conducive to bacterial survival and multiplication, rather than attempting to kill them with chemicals. Bacteria can increase in number very quickly, which enables them to [[evolution|evolve]] rapidly. Should some bacteria survive a chemical attack, they give rise to new generations composed completely of bacteria that have resistance to the particular chemical used. Under a sustained chemical attack, the surviving bacteria in successive generations are increasingly resistant to the chemical used, and ultimately the chemical is rendered ineffective. For this reason, some question the wisdom of impregnating cloths, [[cutting board]]s and worktops in the home with [[bactericidal]] chemicals.{{Citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\n==Types==\n\n===Air disinfectants===\nAir disinfectants are typically chemical substances capable of disinfecting microorganisms suspended in the air. Disinfectants are generally assumed to be limited to use on surfaces, but that is not the case.  In 1928, a study found that airborne microorganisms could be killed using mists of dilute bleach.<ref name=\"bacterialaction\">For a review of the early work in this field, see: {{cite journal |vauthors=Robertson OH, Bigg E, Puck TT, Miller BF |title= The bactericidal action of propylene glycol vapor on microorganisms suspended in air. i |journal= Journal of Experimental Medicine |volume=75 |pages=593\u2013610 |date=June 1942  |pmid=19871209 |doi=10.1084/jem.75.6.593 |issue= 6 |pmc= 2135271}}</ref> An air disinfectant must be dispersed either as an [[aerosol]] or [[vapour]]<!--WP:ENGVAR: please WP:RETAIN--> at a sufficient concentration in the air to cause the number of viable infectious microorganisms to be significantly reduced.\n\nIn the 1940s and early 1950s, further studies showed inactivation of diverse [[bacteria]], [[influenza virus]], and ''[[Penicillium chrysogenum]]'' (previously ''P. notatum'') [[Mold (fungus)|mold]] [[fungus]] using various glycols, principally [[propylene glycol]] and [[triethylene glycol]].<ref name=\"bactericidaleffects\">For a review through 1952 see: {{cite journal |vauthors=Lester W, Dunklin E, Robertson OH |title= Bactericidal effects of propylene and triethylene glycol vapors on airborne Escherichia coli |journal= Science |volume=115 |pages=379\u2013382 |date=April 1952 |pmid= 17770126 |doi=10.1126/Science.115.2988.379 |issue= 2988|bibcode=1952Sci...115..379L }}</ref>  In principle, these chemical substances are ideal air disinfectants because they have both high lethality to microorganisms and low mammalian toxicity.<ref name=\"propyleneglycol\">For a review of the toxicity of propylene glycol, see:  {{cite journal |author= United States Environmental Protection Agency |title= Reregistration eligibility decision for propylene glycol and dipropylene glycol |volume= EPA 739-R-06-002 |date=September 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"triethyleneglycol\">For a review of the toxicity of triethylene glycol, see:  {{cite journal |author= United States Environmental Protection Agency |title= Reregistration eligibility decision for triethylene glycol |volume= EPA 739-R-05-002 |date=September 2005}}</ref>\n\nAlthough glycols are effective air disinfectants in controlled laboratory environments, it is more difficult to use them effectively in real-world environments because the disinfection of air is sensitive to continuous action.  Continuous action in real-world environments with outside air exchanges at door, HVAC, and window interfaces, and in the presence of materials that adsorb and remove glycols from the air, poses engineering challenges that are not critical for surface disinfection.  The engineering challenge associated with creating a sufficient concentration of the glycol vapours in the air have not to date been sufficiently addressed.<ref name=\"progressincontrol\">{{cite journal |author= Committee on Research Standards |title= Air Sanitation (Progress in the Control of Air-Borne Infections) |journal= American Journal of Public Health and the Nation's Health |volume=40 |pages=82\u201388 |date=May 1950 |pmid= 15418852 |doi= 10.2105/AJPH.40.5_Pt_2.82 |issue= 5 Pt 2 |pmc= 1528669}}</ref><ref name=\"factorsofimportance\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Lester W, Kaye S, Robertson OH, Dunklin EW |title= Factors of Importance in the Use of Triethylene Glycol Vapor for Aerial Disinfection |journal= American Journal of Public Health and the Nation's Health |volume=40 |pages=813\u2013820 |date=July 1950 |pmid= 15425663 |doi= 10.2105/AJPH.40.7.813 |issue= 7 |pmc= 1528959}}</ref>\n\n===Alcohols===\n[[File:Automat do dezynfekcji r\u0105k w 60-tysi\u0119cznym Tomaszowie Mazowieckim, w wojew\u00f3dztwie \u0142\u00f3dzkim.jpg|thumb|Automatic hand sanitizer in [[Tomasz\u00f3w Mazowiecki]], Poland ]]\n{{see also|Hand sanitizer}}\n[[Alcohol]] and alcohol plus [[Quaternary ammonium cation]] based compounds comprise a class of proven surface sanitizers and disinfectants approved by the [[EPA]] and the [[Centers for Disease Control]] for use as a hospital grade disinfectant.<ref name=\"cdc.gov\">{{cite web | url=https://www.cdc.gov/infectioncontrol/guidelines/disinfection/index.html | title=Disinfection & Sterilization Guidelines | publisher=CDC | work=Guidelines Library: Infection Control | date=December 28, 2016 | accessdate=January 12, 2018 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180112160244/https://www.cdc.gov/infectioncontrol/guidelines/disinfection/index.html | archivedate=12 January 2018 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Alcohols are most effective when combined with [[distilled water]] to facilitate diffusion through the cell membrane; 100% alcohol typically denatures only external membrane proteins.<ref name=\"foodsafety\"> {{cite web |url=http://vm.cfsan.fda.gov/~dms/a2z-b.html |title= Food Safety A to Z Reference Guide-B | publisher=[[FDA]] [[CFSAN]]|accessdate=10 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060103105715/http://vm.cfsan.fda.gov/~dms/a2z-b.html |archivedate=3 January 2006 }}</ref>  A mixture of 70% ethanol or [[isopropanol]] diluted in water is effective against a wide spectrum of bacteria, though higher concentrations are often needed to disinfect wet surfaces.<ref name=\"alcoholreview\">{{cite journal |author=Moorer WR |title=Antiviral activity of alcohol for surface disinfection |journal=[[International Journal of Dental Hygiene]] |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=138\u201342 |date=August 2003 |pmid=16451513 |doi=10.1034/j.1601-5037.2003.00032.x}}</ref>  Additionally, high-concentration mixtures (such as 80% ethanol + 5% isopropanol) are required to effectively inactivate lipid-enveloped viruses (such as [[HIV]], [[hepatitis B]], and [[hepatitis C]]).<ref name=\"foodsafety\"/><ref name=\"alcoholreview\"/><ref name=\"virucidal\">{{cite journal |vauthors=van Engelenburg FA, Terpstra FG, Schuitemaker H, Moorer WR |title=The virucidal spectrum of a high concentration alcohol mixture |journal=[[The Journal of Hospital Infection]] |volume=51 |issue=2 |pages=121\u20135 |date=June 2002 |pmid=12090799 |doi=10.1053/jhin.2002.1211}}</ref><ref name=\"virucidal\"/><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Lages SL, Ramakrishnan MA, Goyal SM |title=In-vivo efficacy of hand sanitisers against feline calicivirus: a surrogate for norovirus |journal=The Journal of Hospital Infection |volume=68 |issue=2 |pages=159\u201363 |date=February 2008 |pmid=18207605 |doi=10.1016/j.jhin.2007.11.018}}</ref> \n\nThe efficacy of alcohol is enhanced when in solution with the wetting agent [[dodecanoic acid]] (coconut soap).  The synergistic effect of 29.4% ethanol with dodecanoic acid is effective against a broad spectrum of bacteria, fungi, and viruses.  Further testing is being performed against [[Clostridium difficile (bacteria)|Clostridium difficile]] (C.Diff) spores with higher concentrations of ethanol and dodecanoic acid, which proved effective with a contact time of ten minutes.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.urthpro.com | title = Clean & Disinfect Mold, Bacteria & Viruses in any Environment | publisher=UrthPRO| accessdate = November 18, 2010| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202151102/http://www.urthpro.com/| archivedate=February 2, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Aldehydes===\n[[Aldehyde]]s, such as [[formaldehyde]] and [[glutaraldehyde]], have a wide microbiocidal activity and are [[sporicidal]] and [[fungicidal]]. They are partly inactivated by organic matter and have slight residual activity.\n\nSome bacteria have developed resistance to glutaraldehyde, and it has been found that glutaraldehyde can cause asthma and other health hazards, hence [[ortho-phthalaldehyde]] is replacing glutaraldehyde.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n\n===Oxidizing agents===\n\n[[redox|Oxidizing agents]] act by oxidizing the cell membrane of microorganisms, which results in a loss of structure and leads to cell [[lysis]] and death.  A large number of disinfectants operate in this way. [[Chlorine]] and [[oxygen]] are strong oxidizers, so their compounds figure heavily here.\n\n*[[Electrolyzed water]] or \"Anolyte\" is an oxidizing, acidic hypochlorite solution made by [[electrolysis]] of [[sodium chloride]] into [[sodium hypochlorite]] and hypochlorous acid. Anolyte has an oxidation-reduction potential of +600 to +1200 mV and a typical pH range of 3.5\u2013\u20138.5, but the most potent solution is produced at a controlled pH 5.0\u20136.3 where the predominant oxychlorine species is [[hypochlorous acid]].\n*[[Hydrogen peroxide]] is used in [[hospital]]s to disinfect surfaces and it is used in solution alone or in combination with other chemicals as a high level disinfectant. Hydrogen peroxide is sometimes mixed with [[colloidal silver]]. It is often preferred because it causes far fewer [[allergic]] reactions than alternative disinfectants. Also used in the food packaging industry to disinfect foil containers. A 3% solution is also used as an antiseptic.\n* [[Vaporized hydrogen peroxide|Hydrogen peroxide vapor]] is used as a [[Sterilization (microbiology)|medical sterilant]] and as room disinfectant. Hydrogen peroxide has the advantage that it decomposes to form oxygen and water thus leaving no long term residues, but hydrogen peroxide as with most other strong oxidants is hazardous, and solutions are a primary irritant. The vapor is hazardous to the respiratory system and eyes and consequently the [[Occupational Safety and Health Administration|OSHA]] permissible exposure limit is 1 ppm (29 CFR 1910.1000 Table Z-1) calculated as an eight-hour time weighted average and the [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health|NIOSH]] immediately dangerous to life and health limit is 75 ppm.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/idlh/intridl4.html |title=CDC - Immediately Dangerous to Life or Health Concentrations (IDLH): Chemical Listing and Documentation of Revised IDLH Values - NIOSH Publications and Products |publisher=Cdc.gov |date=31 July 2009 |accessdate=10 November 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117012820/http://www.cdc.gov/niosh/idlh/intridl4.html |archivedate=17 November 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Therefore, engineering controls, personal protective equipment, gas monitoring etc. should be employed where high concentrations of hydrogen peroxide are used in the workplace. Vaporized hydrogen peroxide is one of the chemicals approved for decontamination of anthrax spores from contaminated buildings, such as occurred during the [[2001 anthrax attacks]] in the U.S. It has also been shown to be effective in removing exotic animal viruses, such as avian influenza and [[Newcastle disease]] from equipment and surfaces.\n* The antimicrobial action of hydrogen peroxide can be enhanced by [[surfactant]]s and organic acids. The resulting chemistry is known as Accelerated Hydrogen Peroxide. A 2% solution, stabilized for extended use, achieves high-level disinfection in 5 minutes, and is suitable for disinfecting medical equipment made from hard plastic, such as in [[endoscope]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |author= Omidbakhsh|title= A new peroxide-based flexible endoscope-compatible high-level disinfectant |journal=American Journal of Infection Control |volume=34 |issue=9 |pages=571\u2013577 |year=2006 | pmid=17097451 |doi= 10.1016/j.ajic.2006.02.003|display-authors=etal}}</ref>  The evidence available suggests that products based on Accelerated Hydrogen Peroxide, apart from being good germicides, are safer for humans and benign to the environment.<ref>{{cite journal |author= Sattar|title= A product based on accelerated hydrogen peroxide: Evidence for broad-spectrum activity |journal=Canadian Journal of Infection Control |pages=123\u2013130 |date=Winter 1998 |display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n*[[Ozone]] is a gas used for disinfecting water, laundry, foods, air, and surfaces. It is chemically aggressive and destroys many organic compounds, resulting in rapid decolorization and deodorization in addition to disinfection. Ozone decomposes relatively quickly. However, due to this characteristic of ozone, tap water chlorination cannot be entirely replaced by ozonation, as the ozone would decompose already in the water piping. Instead, it is used to remove the bulk of oxidizable matter from the water, which would produce small amounts of [[organochloride]]s if treated with chlorine only. Regardless, ozone has a very wide range of applications from municipal to industrial water treatment due to its powerful reactivity. \n*[[Potassium permanganate]] (KMnO<sub>4</sub>) is a purplish-black crystalline powder that colours everything it touches, through a strong oxidising action. This includes staining \"stainless\" steel, which somehow limits its use and makes it necessary to use plastic or glass containers.  It is used to disinfect [[aquarium]]s and is  used in some community swimming pools as a foot disinfectant before entering the pool. Typically, a large shallow basin of KMnO<sub>4</sub> / water solution is kept near the pool ladder. Participants are required to step in the basin and then go into the pool. Additionally, it is widely used to disinfect community water ponds and wells in tropical countries, as well as to disinfect the mouth before pulling out teeth. It can be applied to wounds in dilute solution.\n\n=== Peroxy and peroxo acids ===\n[[Peroxy acid|Peroxycarboxylic acids and inorganic peroxo acids]] are strong oxidants and extremely effective disinfectants.\n\n* [[Peroxyformic acid]]\n* [[Peracetic acid]]\n* [[Peroxypropionic acid]]\n* [[Monoperoxyglutaric acid]]\n* [[Monoperoxysuccinic acid]]\n* [[Peroxybenzoic acid]]\n* [[Peroxyanisic acid]]\n* [[meta-Chloroperoxybenzoic acid|Chloroperbenzoic acid]]\n* [[Monoperoxyphthalic acid]]\n* [[Peroxymonosulfuric acid]]\n\n===Phenolics===\n[[Phenols|Phenolics]] are active ingredients in some household disinfectants. They are also found in some mouthwashes and in disinfectant soap and handwashes. Phenols are toxic to cats<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peteducation.com/article.cfm?c=2+1677&aid=2243|title=Phenol and Phenolic Poisoning in Dogs and Cats|website=www.peteducation.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919033206/http://www.peteducation.com/article.cfm?c=2+1677&aid=2243|archivedate=19 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and newborn humans<ref>{{cite web|url=https://toxnet.nlm.nih.gov/cgi-bin/sis/search/a?dbs+hsdb:@term+@DOCNO+113|title=PHENOL - National Library of Medicine HSDB Database|website=toxnet.nlm.nih.gov|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201031619/https://toxnet.nlm.nih.gov/cgi-bin/sis/search/a?dbs+hsdb:@term+@DOCNO+113|archivedate=1 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n* [[Phenol]] is probably the oldest known disinfectant as it was first used by [[Joseph Lister, 1st Baron Lister|Lister]], when it was called carbolic acid. It is rather corrosive to the skin and sometimes toxic to sensitive people. Impure preparations of phenol were originally made from [[coal tar]], and these contained low concentrations of other [[aromatic hydrocarbon]]s including [[benzene]], which is an [[International Agency for Research on Cancer|IARC]] [[List of IARC Group 1 carcinogens|Group 1]] [[carcinogen]].\n* [[2-Phenylphenol|''o''-Phenylphenol]] is often used instead of [[phenol]], since it is somewhat less corrosive.\n* [[Chloroxylenol]] is the principal ingredient in [[Dettol]], a household disinfectant and [[antiseptic]].\n* [[Hexachlorophene]] is a phenolic that was once used as a germicidal additive to some household products but was banned due to suspected harmful effects.\n* [[Thymol]], derived from the herb thyme, is the active ingredient in some \"broad spectrum\" disinfectants that often bear ecological claims. It is used as a stabilizer in pharmaceutic preparations. It has been used for its antiseptic, antibacterial, and antifungal actions, and was formerly used as a vermifuge.<ref name=\"nih.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov|title=The PubChem Project|website=pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808222031/http://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/|archivedate=8 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n* [[Amylmetacresol]] is found in [[Strepsils]], a throat disinfectant.\n* Although not a phenol, [[2,4-dichlorobenzyl alcohol]] has similar effects as phenols, but it cannot inactivate viruses.\n\n===Quaternary ammonium compounds===\n\n[[Quaternary ammonium compounds]] (\"quats\"), such as [[benzalkonium chloride]], are a large group of related compounds. Some concentrated formulations have been shown to be effective low-level disinfectants. Quaternary ammonia at or above 200ppm plus alcohol solutions exhibit efficacy against difficult to kill non-enveloped viruses such as [[norovirus]], [[rotavirus]], or [[polio virus]].<ref name=\"cdc.gov\"/>  Newer synergous, low-alcohol formulations are highly effective broad-spectrum disinfectants with quick contact times (3\u20135 minutes) against bacteria, enveloped viruses, pathogenic fungi, and [[mycobacteria]].  Quats are biocides that also kill algae and are used as an additive in large-scale industrial water systems to minimize undesired biological growth.\n\n=== Inorganic compounds ===\n==== Chlorine ====\nThis group comprises aqueous solution of [[chlorine]], [[hypochlorite]], or [[hypochlorous acid]]. Occasionally, chlorine-releasing compounds and their salts are included in this group. Frequently, a concentration of < 1 ppm of available chlorine is sufficient to kill bacteria and viruses, spores and mycobacteria requiring higher concentrations.\nChlorine has been used for applications, such as the deactivation of pathogens in drinking water, swimming pool water and wastewater, for the disinfection of household areas and for textile bleaching<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lenntech.com/processes/disinfection/chemical/disinfectants-chlorine.htm|title=chlorine as disinfectant for water|website=www.lenntech.com|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref>\n* [[Sodium hypochlorite]]\n* [[Calcium hypochlorite]]\n* [[Monochloramine]]\n* [[Chloramine-T]]\n* [[Trichloroisocyanuric acid]]\n* [[Chlorine dioxide]]\n* [[Hypochlorous acid]]\n\n==== Iodine ====\n* [[Iodine]]\n* [[Iodophor]]s\n==== Acids and bases ====\n* [[Sodium hydroxide]]\n* [[Potassium hydroxide]]\n* [[Calcium hydroxide]]\n* [[Magnesium hydroxide]]\n* [[Sulfurous acid]]\n* [[Sulfur dioxide]]\n====Metals====\n{{main|Oligodynamic effect}}\n\n=== Terpenes ===\n* [[Thymol]]\n* [[Pine oil]]\n\n===Other===\nThe [[biguanide]] [[polymer]] [[polyaminopropyl biguanide]] is specifically bactericidal at very low concentrations (10&nbsp;mg/l). It has a unique method of action: The polymer strands are incorporated into the bacterial cell wall, which disrupts the membrane and reduces its permeability, which has a lethal effect to bacteria. It is also known to bind to bacterial DNA, alter its transcription, and cause lethal DNA damage.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Allen MJ, White GF, Morby AP |title=The response of Escherichia coli to exposure to the biocide polyhexamethylene biguanide |journal=Microbiology |volume=152 |issue=Pt 4 |pages=989\u20131000 |year=2006 |pmid=16549663 |doi=10.1099/mic.0.28643-0 |url=http://mic.sgmjournals.org/cgi/content/full/152/4/989 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526161153/http://mic.sgmjournals.org/cgi/content/full/152/4/989 |archivedate=26 May 2011 |df=dmy-all |doi-access=free }}</ref> It has very low toxicity to higher organisms such as human cells, which have more complex and protective membranes.\n\nCommon [[sodium bicarbonate]] (NaHCO<sub>3</sub>) has antifungal properties,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Zamani M, Sharifi Tehrani A, Ali Abadi AA |title=Evaluation of antifungal activity of carbonate and bicarbonate salts alone or in combination with biocontrol agents in control of citrus green mold |journal=Communications in Agricultural and Applied Biological Sciences |volume=72 |issue=4 |pages=773\u20137 |year=2007 |pmid=18396809}}</ref> and some antiviral and antibacterial properties,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Malik YS, Goyal SM |title=Virucidal efficacy of sodium bicarbonate on a food contact surface against feline calicivirus, a norovirus surrogate |journal=International Journal of Food Microbiology |volume=109 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=160\u20133 |date=May 2006 |pmid=16540196 |doi=10.1016/j.ijfoodmicro.2005.08.033}}</ref> though those are too weak to be effective at a home environment.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=William A. Rutala |author2=Susan L. Barbee |author3=Newman C. Aguiar |author4=Mark D. Sobsey |author5=David J. Weber |year=2000 |title=Antimicrobial Activity of Home Disinfectants and Natural Products Against Potential Human Pathogens |journal=Infection Control and Hospital Epidemiology |volume=21 |issue=1 |pages=33\u201338 |publisher=The University of Chicago Press on behalf of The Society for Healthcare Epidemiology of America |doi=10.1086/501694 |pmid=10656352 |jstor=10}}</ref>\n\n===Non-chemical===\n[[Ultraviolet germicidal irradiation]] is the use of high-intensity shortwave [[ultraviolet light]] for disinfecting smooth surfaces such as dental tools, but not porous materials that are opaque to the light such as wood or foam. Ultraviolet light is also used for municipal [[water treatment]]. Ultraviolet light fixtures are often present in [[microbiology]] labs, and are activated only when there are no occupants in a room (e.g., at night).\n\nHeat treatment can be used for disinfection and sterilization.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://ehs.research.uiowa.edu/87-heat-disinfection-and-sterilization | title = Heat Disinfection and Sterilization | publisher = [[University of Iowa]], Environmental Health & Safety | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170108190620/https://ehs.research.uiowa.edu/87-heat-disinfection-and-sterilization | archivedate = 8 January 2017 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|Sunlight}}The phrase \"sunlight is the best disinfectant\" was [[Other People's Money and How the Bankers Use It|popularized in 1913]] by [[United States Supreme Court]] Justice [[Louis Brandeis]] and later advocates of [[government transparency]]. While sunlight's ultraviolet rays can act as a disinfectant, the Earth's [[ozone layer]] blocks the rays' most effective wavelengths. Ultraviolet light-emitting machines, such as those used to disinfect some hospital rooms, make for better disinfectants than sunlight.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=McCarthy |first1=Ciara |title=Is Sunlight Actually the Best Disinfectant? |work=Slate |date=9 August 2013 |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/explainer/2013/08/sunlight_is_the_best_disinfectant_not_exactly.html |issn=1091-2339 |df=mdy-all |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305042551/http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/explainer/2013/08/sunlight_is_the_best_disinfectant_not_exactly.html |archivedate=5 March 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Measurements of effectiveness==\nOne way to compare disinfectants is to compare how well they do against a known disinfectant and rate them accordingly. Phenol is the standard, and the corresponding rating system is called the \"[[Phenol coefficient]]\". The disinfectant to be tested is compared with phenol on a standard microbe (usually ''[[Salmonella typhi]]'' or ''[[Staphylococcus aureus]]''). Disinfectants that are more effective than phenol have a coefficient &gt; 1. Those that are less effective have a coefficient &lt; 1.\n\nThe standard European approach for disinfectant validation consists of a basic suspension test, a quantitative suspension test (with low and high levels of organic material added to act as \u2018interfering substances\u2019) and a two part simulated-use surface test.<ref name=Sandle>{{cite book | editor = Sandle T | title = The CDC Handbook: A Guide to Cleaning and Disinfecting Cleanrooms  | edition = 1st | publisher = Grosvenor House Publishing Limited | year = 2012 | isbn = 978-1781487686}}</ref>\n\nA less specific measurement of effectiveness is the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) classification into either ''high'', ''intermediate'' or ''low'' levels of disinfection. \"High-level disinfection kills all organisms, except high levels of bacterial spores\" and is done with a chemical germicide marketed as a sterilant by the U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA). \"Intermediate-level disinfection kills mycobacteria, most viruses, and bacteria with a chemical germicide registered as a 'tuberculocide' by the Environmental Protection Agency. Low-level disinfection kills some viruses and bacteria with a chemical germicide registered as a hospital disinfectant by the EPA.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/HAI/prevent/sd_medicalDevices.html |title=Sterilization or Disinfection of Medical Devices |author=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=21 December 2012 |website=CDC |accessdate=20 July 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130720040938/http://www.cdc.gov/HAI/prevent/sd_medicalDevices.html |archivedate=20 July 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAn alternative assessment is to measure the Minimum inhibitory concentrations (MICs) of disinfectants against selected (and representative) microbial species, such as through the use of microbroth dilution testing.<ref>{{Cite journal|vauthors=Vijayakumar R, Kannan VV, Sandle T, Manoharan C\n |title=In vitro Antifungal Efficacy of Biguanides and Quaternary Ammonium Compounds against Cleanroom Fungal Isolates|journal=[[PDA (journal)|PDA J Pharm Sci Technol]] |volume=66 |issue=3 |pages=236\u201342|date=May 2012 |doi=10.5731/pdajpst.2012.00866}}</ref> However, those methods are obtained at standard inoculum levels without considering the inoculum effect. More informative methods are nowadays in demand to determine the minimum disinfectant dose as a function of the density of the target microbial species <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Garc\u00eda|first1=MR|last2=Cabo|first2=ML|title=Optimization of ''E. coli'' Inactivation by Benzalkonium Chloride Reveals the Importance of Quantifying the Inoculum Effect on Chemical Disinfection.|journal=Frontiers in Microbiology|date=June 2018|volume=9|pages=1259|doi=10.3389/fmicb.2018.01259|pmid=29997577|pmc=6028699}}</ref>.\n\n===Health Warning for Human Ingestion, Injection, and Inhalation===\nThe April 23, 2020 [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] meeting addressed by President [[Donald Trump]] included conjecture that injecting or ingesting disinfectants could clean the body from [[coronavirus]] infection. However, this was emphatically denounced by health professionals due to grave danger to the human body.<ref>https://7news.com.au/lifestyle/health-wellbeing/coronavirus-dettol-and-lysol-issue-health-warning-after-donald-trumps-disinfectant-comments-c-998618</ref><ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52411706</ref>\n\n==Home disinfectants==\n{{cleanup|section|reason=Overuse of the definite article, and non-encyclopedic style|date=February 2015}}\n\nThe most cost-effective home disinfectant is [[Bleach|chlorine bleach]] (typically a >10% solution of [[sodium hypochlorite]]), which is effective against most common [[pathogens]], including disinfectant-resistant organisms such as [[tuberculosis]] ([[mycobacterium tuberculosis]]), [[hepatitis]] B and C, [[fungi]], and antibiotic-resistant strains of [[staphylococcus]] and [[enterococcus]]. It has disinfectant action against some [[Parasites|parasitic organisms]].<ref>[http://www.epa.gov/oppad001/chemregindex.htm EPA's Registered Sterilizers, Tuberculocides, and Antimicrobial Products Against [[HIV]]-1, and Hepatitis B and Hepatitis C Viruses.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930061054/http://www.epa.gov/oppad001/chemregindex.htm |date=30 September 2015 }} (Obtained 4 January 2006)</ref>{{Failed verification|date=September 2018}}\n\nThe benefits of chlorine bleach include its inexpensive and fast acting nature. However it is harmful to mucous membranes and skin upon contact, has a strong odour; is not effective against ''[[Giardia lamblia]]'' and ''[[Cryptosporidium]]''; and combination with other cleaning products such as ammonia and [[vinegar]] can generate noxious gases like [[chlorine]]. The best practice is not to add anything to household bleach except water. As with most disinfectants, the area requiring disinfection should be cleaned before the application of the chlorine bleach, as the presence of organic materials may inactivate chlorine bleach.\n\nThe use of some antimicrobials such as [[triclosan]], is controversial because it may lead to [[antimicrobial resistance]]. The use of chlorine bleach and alcohol disinfectants does not cause [[antimicrobial resistance]] as it denatures the protein of the microbe upon contact.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://watoxics.org/healthy-living/healthy-homes-gardens-1/factsheets/antimicrobials |title=Antimicrobial Products: Who Needs Them? \u2014 Washington Toxics Coalition |publisher=Watoxics.org |date=15 September 1997 |accessdate=10 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710230146/http://watoxics.org/healthy-living/healthy-homes-gardens-1/factsheets/antimicrobials |archivedate=10 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Drug resistance]]\n* [[Diethylene glycol]] - a raw material for air [[sanitation]]\n* [[Hand sanitizer]]\n* [[Hygiene]]\n* [[List of cleaning products]]\n* [[Sanitation Standard Operating Procedures]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal | title = Virus resistance in a hospital environment: overview of the virucide activity of disinfectants used in liquid form | journal = Annales de Biologie Clinique | date = Nov\u2013Dec 1998 | first = H. | last = Soule |author2=D. L. Duc |author3=M. R. Mallaret |author4=B. Chanzy |author5=A. Charvier |author6=B. Gratacap-Cavallier |author7=P. Morand |author8=J. M. Seigneurin  | volume = 56 | issue = 6 | pages = 693\u2013703 | id =  | language = French | pmid=9853028}}\n*{{cite book | editor = Sandle, T. | title = The CDC Handbook: A Guide to Cleaning and Disinfecting Cleanrooms  | edition = 1st | publisher = Grosvenor House Publishing Limited | year = 2012 | isbn = 978-1781487686}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100724144955/http://www.mansfield.ohio-state.edu/~sabedon/black12.htm Ohio State University lecture on Sterilization and Disinfection]\n* [http://www.unitedsanitizing.com/index.php/technical/frequently-asked-questions/ NAV-CO2 as a disinfection method using Alcohols and Quaternary Ammonia]* \n* [http://www.housekeepingchannel.com/showarticle.php?id=253 What Germs Are We Killing? Testing and Classifying Disinfectants]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090823195546/http://www.bccdc.org/downloads/pdf/epid/reports/CDManual_DisinfectntSelectnGuidelines_sep2003_nov05-03.pdf Disinfectant Selection Guide]\n* [http://www.newton.dep.anl.gov/askasci/chem03/chem03856.htm Disinfectant and Non-Chlorine Bleach]\u2014Office of DOE Science Education\n* [http://www.wien.gv.at/english/environment/protection/oekokauf/disinfectants/index.html The Viennese Database for Disinfectants (WIDES Database)]\n\n{{Antiseptics and disinfectants}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Disinfectants| ]]\n[[Category:Hygiene]]\n[[Category:Bactericides]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Antimicrobial agents that inactivate or destroy microorganisms}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{about|antimicrobial agents|the Macintosh anti-virus software|Disinfectant (software)}}\n[[File:Disinfection with mop.jpg|thumb|Disinfection of a floor using disinfectant liquid applied using a [[mop]].]]\n[[File:Resistance of Microbes to Disinfectants.png|thumb|Levels of resistance of microbes to disinfectants.]]\n'''Disinfectants''' are [[antimicrobial]] agents designed to inactivate or destroy [[microorganisms]] on inert surfaces.<ref name=\"cdc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/oralhealth/infectioncontrol/glossary.htm|accessdate=19 April 2016|title=Division of Oral Health - Infection Control Glossary|publisher=U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413120331/http://www.cdc.gov/oralhealth/infectioncontrol/glossary.htm|archivedate=13 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Disinfection does not necessarily kill all microorganisms, especially resistant [[endospore|bacterial spores]]; it is less effective than [[sterilization (microbiology)|sterilization]], which is an extreme physical or chemical process that kills all types of life.<ref name=\"cdc\"/> Disinfectants are different from other antimicrobial agents such as [[antibiotic]]s, which destroy microorganisms within the body, and [[antiseptic]]s, which destroy microorganisms on living [[biological tissue|tissue]]. Disinfectants are also different from [[biocide]]s \u2014 the latter are intended to destroy all forms of life, not just microorganisms.\nDisinfectants work by destroying the cell wall of microbes or interfering with their metabolism.\n\nSanitizers are substances that simultaneously clean and disinfect.<ref name=\"FSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.food.gov.uk/safety-hygiene/cleaning|title=Cleaning|publisher=Fodd Dtandards Agency|access-date=12 December 2019}}, (2009), ''[[Mid Sussex|Mid Sussex District Council]]'', UK.</ref> Disinfectants kill more germs than sanitizers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Green Cleaning, Sanitizing, and Disinfecting: A Curriculum for Early Care and Education |url=https://www.epa.gov/sites/production/files/documents/ece_curriculum_7.2013_for_uploading.pdf |accessdate=8 April 2019}}</ref> Disinfectants are frequently used in hospitals, dental surgeries, kitchens, and bathrooms to kill infectious organisms.\n\nBacterial [[endospore]]s are most resistant to disinfectants, but some [[fungi]], [[virus]]es and [[bacteria]] also possess some resistance.\n\n[[File:DISINFECTANT PIC.svg|thumb| Disinfectants are used to rapidly kill bacteria. They kill off the bacteria by causing the proteins to become damaged and outer layers of the bacteria cell to rupture. The DNA material subsequently leaks out.]]\n\nIn [[sewage treatment|wastewater treatment]], a disinfection step with [[chlorine]], [[Ultra-violet radiation|ultra-violet (UV) radiation]] or [[ozonation]] can be included as tertiary treatment to remove [[pathogens]] from wastewater, for example if it is to be discharged to a river or the sea where there body contact immersion recreations is practiced (Europe) or reused to irrigate golf courses (US). An alternative term used in the [[sanitation]] sector for disinfection of waste streams, [[sewage sludge]] or [[septage|fecal sludge]] is '''sanitisation''' [[American and British English spelling differences|or]] '''sanitization'''.\n\n==Properties==\nA perfect disinfectant would also offer complete and full microbiological [[sterilization (microbiology)|sterilisation]], without harming humans and useful form of life, be inexpensive, and noncorrosive. However, most disinfectants are also, by nature, potentially harmful (even [[toxic]]) to humans or animals. Most modern household disinfectants contain [[denatonium]], an exceptionally bitter substance added to discourage ingestion, as a safety measure. Those that are used indoors should never be mixed with other cleaning products as [[chemical reaction]]s can occur.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.state.nj.us/health/eoh/cehsweb/bleach_fs.pdf |accessdate=19 April 2016 |title=Common Cleaning Products May Be Dangerous When Mixed |publisher=New Jersey Department of Health and Senior Services |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323153736/http://www.state.nj.us/health/eoh/cehsweb/bleach_fs.pdf |archivedate=23 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The choice of disinfectant to be used depends on the particular situation. Some disinfectants have a wide spectrum (kill many different types of microorganisms), while others kill a smaller range of disease-causing organisms but are preferred for other properties (they may be non-corrosive, non-toxic, or inexpensive).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.health.ny.gov/professionals/protocols_and_guidelines/antibiotic_resistance/docs/hospital_disinfectants_for_general_disinfection_of_environmental_surfaces.pdf |accessdate=19 April 2016 |title=Hospital Disinfectants for General Disinfection of Environmental Surfaces |publisher=New York State Department of Health |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924025446/http://www.health.ny.gov/professionals/protocols_and_guidelines/antibiotic_resistance/docs/hospital_disinfectants_for_general_disinfection_of_environmental_surfaces.pdf |archivedate=24 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThere are arguments for creating or maintaining conditions that are not conducive to bacterial survival and multiplication, rather than attempting to kill them with chemicals. Bacteria can increase in number very quickly, which enables them to [[evolution|evolve]] rapidly. Should some bacteria survive a chemical attack, they give rise to new generations composed completely of bacteria that have resistance to the particular chemical used. Under a sustained chemical attack, the surviving bacteria in successive generations are increasingly resistant to the chemical used, and ultimately the chemical is rendered ineffective. For this reason, some question the wisdom of impregnating cloths, [[cutting board]]s and worktops in the home with [[bactericidal]] chemicals.{{Citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\n==Types==\n\n===Air disinfectants===\nAir disinfectants are typically chemical substances capable of disinfecting microorganisms suspended in the air. Disinfectants are generally assumed to be limited to use on surfaces, but that is not the case.  In 1928, a study found that airborne microorganisms could be killed using mists of dilute bleach.<ref name=\"bacterialaction\">For a review of the early work in this field, see: {{cite journal |vauthors=Robertson OH, Bigg E, Puck TT, Miller BF |title= The bactericidal action of propylene glycol vapor on microorganisms suspended in air. i |journal= Journal of Experimental Medicine |volume=75 |pages=593\u2013610 |date=June 1942  |pmid=19871209 |doi=10.1084/jem.75.6.593 |issue= 6 |pmc= 2135271}}</ref> An air disinfectant must be dispersed either as an [[aerosol]] or [[vapour]]<!--WP:ENGVAR: please WP:RETAIN--> at a sufficient concentration in the air to cause the number of viable infectious microorganisms to be significantly reduced.\n\nIn the 1940s and early 1950s, further studies showed inactivation of diverse [[bacteria]], [[influenza virus]], and ''[[Penicillium chrysogenum]]'' (previously ''P. notatum'') [[Mold (fungus)|mold]] [[fungus]] using various glycols, principally [[propylene glycol]] and [[triethylene glycol]].<ref name=\"bactericidaleffects\">For a review through 1952 see: {{cite journal |vauthors=Lester W, Dunklin E, Robertson OH |title= Bactericidal effects of propylene and triethylene glycol vapors on airborne Escherichia coli |journal= Science |volume=115 |pages=379\u2013382 |date=April 1952 |pmid= 17770126 |doi=10.1126/Science.115.2988.379 |issue= 2988|bibcode=1952Sci...115..379L }}</ref>  In principle, these chemical substances are ideal air disinfectants because they have both high lethality to microorganisms and low mammalian toxicity.<ref name=\"propyleneglycol\">For a review of the toxicity of propylene glycol, see:  {{cite journal |author= United States Environmental Protection Agency |title= Reregistration eligibility decision for propylene glycol and dipropylene glycol |volume= EPA 739-R-06-002 |date=September 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"triethyleneglycol\">For a review of the toxicity of triethylene glycol, see:  {{cite journal |author= United States Environmental Protection Agency |title= Reregistration eligibility decision for triethylene glycol |volume= EPA 739-R-05-002 |date=September 2005}}</ref>\n\nAlthough glycols are effective air disinfectants in controlled laboratory environments, it is more difficult to use them effectively in real-world environments because the disinfection of air is sensitive to continuous action.  Continuous action in real-world environments with outside air exchanges at door, HVAC, and window interfaces, and in the presence of materials that adsorb and remove glycols from the air, poses engineering challenges that are not critical for surface disinfection.  The engineering challenge associated with creating a sufficient concentration of the glycol vapours in the air have not to date been sufficiently addressed.<ref name=\"progressincontrol\">{{cite journal |author= Committee on Research Standards |title= Air Sanitation (Progress in the Control of Air-Borne Infections) |journal= American Journal of Public Health and the Nation's Health |volume=40 |pages=82\u201388 |date=May 1950 |pmid= 15418852 |doi= 10.2105/AJPH.40.5_Pt_2.82 |issue= 5 Pt 2 |pmc= 1528669}}</ref><ref name=\"factorsofimportance\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Lester W, Kaye S, Robertson OH, Dunklin EW |title= Factors of Importance in the Use of Triethylene Glycol Vapor for Aerial Disinfection |journal= American Journal of Public Health and the Nation's Health |volume=40 |pages=813\u2013820 |date=July 1950 |pmid= 15425663 |doi= 10.2105/AJPH.40.7.813 |issue= 7 |pmc= 1528959}}</ref>\n\n===Alcohols===\n[[File:Automat do dezynfekcji r\u0105k w 60-tysi\u0119cznym Tomaszowie Mazowieckim, w wojew\u00f3dztwie \u0142\u00f3dzkim.jpg|thumb|Automatic hand sanitizer in [[Tomasz\u00f3w Mazowiecki]], Poland ]]\n{{see also|Hand sanitizer}}\n[[Alcohol]] and alcohol plus [[Quaternary ammonium cation]] based compounds comprise a class of proven surface sanitizers and disinfectants approved by the [[EPA]] and the [[Centers for Disease Control]] for use as a hospital grade disinfectant.<ref name=\"cdc.gov\">{{cite web | url=https://www.cdc.gov/infectioncontrol/guidelines/disinfection/index.html | title=Disinfection & Sterilization Guidelines | publisher=CDC | work=Guidelines Library: Infection Control | date=December 28, 2016 | accessdate=January 12, 2018 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180112160244/https://www.cdc.gov/infectioncontrol/guidelines/disinfection/index.html | archivedate=12 January 2018 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Alcohols are most effective when combined with [[distilled water]] to facilitate diffusion through the cell membrane; 100% alcohol typically denatures only external membrane proteins.<ref name=\"foodsafety\"> {{cite web |url=http://vm.cfsan.fda.gov/~dms/a2z-b.html |title= Food Safety A to Z Reference Guide-B | publisher=[[FDA]] [[CFSAN]]|accessdate=10 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060103105715/http://vm.cfsan.fda.gov/~dms/a2z-b.html |archivedate=3 January 2006 }}</ref>  A mixture of 70% ethanol or [[isopropanol]] diluted in water is effective against a wide spectrum of bacteria, though higher concentrations are often needed to disinfect wet surfaces.<ref name=\"alcoholreview\">{{cite journal |author=Moorer WR |title=Antiviral activity of alcohol for surface disinfection |journal=[[International Journal of Dental Hygiene]] |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=138\u201342 |date=August 2003 |pmid=16451513 |doi=10.1034/j.1601-5037.2003.00032.x}}</ref>  Additionally, high-concentration mixtures (such as 80% ethanol + 5% isopropanol) are required to effectively inactivate lipid-enveloped viruses (such as [[HIV]], [[hepatitis B]], and [[hepatitis C]]).<ref name=\"foodsafety\"/><ref name=\"alcoholreview\"/><ref name=\"virucidal\">{{cite journal |vauthors=van Engelenburg FA, Terpstra FG, Schuitemaker H, Moorer WR |title=The virucidal spectrum of a high concentration alcohol mixture |journal=[[The Journal of Hospital Infection]] |volume=51 |issue=2 |pages=121\u20135 |date=June 2002 |pmid=12090799 |doi=10.1053/jhin.2002.1211}}</ref><ref name=\"virucidal\"/><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Lages SL, Ramakrishnan MA, Goyal SM |title=In-vivo efficacy of hand sanitisers against feline calicivirus: a surrogate for norovirus |journal=The Journal of Hospital Infection |volume=68 |issue=2 |pages=159\u201363 |date=February 2008 |pmid=18207605 |doi=10.1016/j.jhin.2007.11.018}}</ref> \n\nThe efficacy of alcohol is enhanced when in solution with the wetting agent [[dodecanoic acid]] (coconut soap).  The synergistic effect of 29.4% ethanol with dodecanoic acid is effective against a broad spectrum of bacteria, fungi, and viruses.  Further testing is being performed against [[Clostridium difficile (bacteria)|Clostridium difficile]] (C.Diff) spores with higher concentrations of ethanol and dodecanoic acid, which proved effective with a contact time of ten minutes.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.urthpro.com | title = Clean & Disinfect Mold, Bacteria & Viruses in any Environment | publisher=UrthPRO| accessdate = November 18, 2010| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202151102/http://www.urthpro.com/| archivedate=February 2, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Aldehydes===\n[[Aldehyde]]s, such as [[formaldehyde]] and [[glutaraldehyde]], have a wide microbiocidal activity and are [[sporicidal]] and [[fungicidal]]. They are partly inactivated by organic matter and have slight residual activity.\n\nSome bacteria have developed resistance to glutaraldehyde, and it has been found that glutaraldehyde can cause asthma and other health hazards, hence [[ortho-phthalaldehyde]] is replacing glutaraldehyde.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n\n===Oxidizing agents===\n\n[[redox|Oxidizing agents]] act by oxidizing the cell membrane of microorganisms, which results in a loss of structure and leads to cell [[lysis]] and death.  A large number of disinfectants operate in this way. [[Chlorine]] and [[oxygen]] are strong oxidizers, so their compounds figure heavily here.\n\n*[[Electrolyzed water]] or \"Anolyte\" is an oxidizing, acidic hypochlorite solution made by [[electrolysis]] of [[sodium chloride]] into [[sodium hypochlorite]] and hypochlorous acid. Anolyte has an oxidation-reduction potential of +600 to +1200 mV and a typical pH range of 3.5\u2013\u20138.5, but the most potent solution is produced at a controlled pH 5.0\u20136.3 where the predominant oxychlorine species is [[hypochlorous acid]].\n*[[Hydrogen peroxide]] is used in [[hospital]]s to disinfect surfaces and it is used in solution alone or in combination with other chemicals as a high level disinfectant. Hydrogen peroxide is sometimes mixed with [[colloidal silver]]. It is often preferred because it causes far fewer [[allergic]] reactions than alternative disinfectants. Also used in the food packaging industry to disinfect foil containers. A 3% solution is also used as an antiseptic.\n* [[Vaporized hydrogen peroxide|Hydrogen peroxide vapor]] is used as a [[Sterilization (microbiology)|medical sterilant]] and as room disinfectant. Hydrogen peroxide has the advantage that it decomposes to form oxygen and water thus leaving no long term residues, but hydrogen peroxide as with most other strong oxidants is hazardous, and solutions are a primary irritant. The vapor is hazardous to the respiratory system and eyes and consequently the [[Occupational Safety and Health Administration|OSHA]] permissible exposure limit is 1 ppm (29 CFR 1910.1000 Table Z-1) calculated as an eight-hour time weighted average and the [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health|NIOSH]] immediately dangerous to life and health limit is 75 ppm.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/idlh/intridl4.html |title=CDC - Immediately Dangerous to Life or Health Concentrations (IDLH): Chemical Listing and Documentation of Revised IDLH Values - NIOSH Publications and Products |publisher=Cdc.gov |date=31 July 2009 |accessdate=10 November 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117012820/http://www.cdc.gov/niosh/idlh/intridl4.html |archivedate=17 November 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Therefore, engineering controls, personal protective equipment, gas monitoring etc. should be employed where high concentrations of hydrogen peroxide are used in the workplace. Vaporized hydrogen peroxide is one of the chemicals approved for decontamination of anthrax spores from contaminated buildings, such as occurred during the [[2001 anthrax attacks]] in the U.S. It has also been shown to be effective in removing exotic animal viruses, such as avian influenza and [[Newcastle disease]] from equipment and surfaces.\n* The antimicrobial action of hydrogen peroxide can be enhanced by [[surfactant]]s and organic acids. The resulting chemistry is known as Accelerated Hydrogen Peroxide. A 2% solution, stabilized for extended use, achieves high-level disinfection in 5 minutes, and is suitable for disinfecting medical equipment made from hard plastic, such as in [[endoscope]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |author= Omidbakhsh|title= A new peroxide-based flexible endoscope-compatible high-level disinfectant |journal=American Journal of Infection Control |volume=34 |issue=9 |pages=571\u2013577 |year=2006 | pmid=17097451 |doi= 10.1016/j.ajic.2006.02.003|display-authors=etal}}</ref>  The evidence available suggests that products based on Accelerated Hydrogen Peroxide, apart from being good germicides, are safer for humans and benign to the environment.<ref>{{cite journal |author= Sattar|title= A product based on accelerated hydrogen peroxide: Evidence for broad-spectrum activity |journal=Canadian Journal of Infection Control |pages=123\u2013130 |date=Winter 1998 |display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n*[[Ozone]] is a gas used for disinfecting water, laundry, foods, air, and surfaces. It is chemically aggressive and destroys many organic compounds, resulting in rapid decolorization and deodorization in addition to disinfection. Ozone decomposes relatively quickly. However, due to this characteristic of ozone, tap water chlorination cannot be entirely replaced by ozonation, as the ozone would decompose already in the water piping. Instead, it is used to remove the bulk of oxidizable matter from the water, which would produce small amounts of [[organochloride]]s if treated with chlorine only. Regardless, ozone has a very wide range of applications from municipal to industrial water treatment due to its powerful reactivity. \n*[[Potassium permanganate]] (KMnO<sub>4</sub>) is a purplish-black crystalline powder that colours everything it touches, through a strong oxidising action. This includes staining \"stainless\" steel, which somehow limits its use and makes it necessary to use plastic or glass containers.  It is used to disinfect [[aquarium]]s and is  used in some community swimming pools as a foot disinfectant before entering the pool. Typically, a large shallow basin of KMnO<sub>4</sub> / water solution is kept near the pool ladder. Participants are required to step in the basin and then go into the pool. Additionally, it is widely used to disinfect community water ponds and wells in tropical countries, as well as to disinfect the mouth before pulling out teeth. It can be applied to wounds in dilute solution.\n\n=== Peroxy and peroxo acids ===\n[[Peroxy acid|Peroxycarboxylic acids and inorganic peroxo acids]] are strong oxidants and extremely effective disinfectants.\n\n* [[Peroxyformic acid]]\n* [[Peracetic acid]]\n* [[Peroxypropionic acid]]\n* [[Monoperoxyglutaric acid]]\n* [[Monoperoxysuccinic acid]]\n* [[Peroxybenzoic acid]]\n* [[Peroxyanisic acid]]\n* [[meta-Chloroperoxybenzoic acid|Chloroperbenzoic acid]]\n* [[Monoperoxyphthalic acid]]\n* [[Peroxymonosulfuric acid]]\n\n===Phenolics===\n[[Phenols|Phenolics]] are active ingredients in some household disinfectants. They are also found in some mouthwashes and in disinfectant soap and handwashes. Phenols are toxic to cats<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peteducation.com/article.cfm?c=2+1677&aid=2243|title=Phenol and Phenolic Poisoning in Dogs and Cats|website=www.peteducation.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919033206/http://www.peteducation.com/article.cfm?c=2+1677&aid=2243|archivedate=19 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and newborn humans<ref>{{cite web|url=https://toxnet.nlm.nih.gov/cgi-bin/sis/search/a?dbs+hsdb:@term+@DOCNO+113|title=PHENOL - National Library of Medicine HSDB Database|website=toxnet.nlm.nih.gov|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201031619/https://toxnet.nlm.nih.gov/cgi-bin/sis/search/a?dbs+hsdb:@term+@DOCNO+113|archivedate=1 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n* [[Phenol]] is probably the oldest known disinfectant as it was first used by [[Joseph Lister, 1st Baron Lister|Lister]], when it was called carbolic acid. It is rather corrosive to the skin and sometimes toxic to sensitive people. Impure preparations of phenol were originally made from [[coal tar]], and these contained low concentrations of other [[aromatic hydrocarbon]]s including [[benzene]], which is an [[International Agency for Research on Cancer|IARC]] [[List of IARC Group 1 carcinogens|Group 1]] [[carcinogen]].\n* [[2-Phenylphenol|''o''-Phenylphenol]] is often used instead of [[phenol]], since it is somewhat less corrosive.\n* [[Chloroxylenol]] is the principal ingredient in [[Dettol]], a household disinfectant and [[antiseptic]].\n* [[Hexachlorophene]] is a phenolic that was once used as a germicidal additive to some household products but was banned due to suspected harmful effects.\n* [[Thymol]], derived from the herb thyme, is the active ingredient in some \"broad spectrum\" disinfectants that often bear ecological claims. It is used as a stabilizer in pharmaceutic preparations. It has been used for its antiseptic, antibacterial, and antifungal actions, and was formerly used as a vermifuge.<ref name=\"nih.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov|title=The PubChem Project|website=pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808222031/http://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/|archivedate=8 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n* [[Amylmetacresol]] is found in [[Strepsils]], a throat disinfectant.\n* Although not a phenol, [[2,4-dichlorobenzyl alcohol]] has similar effects as phenols, but it cannot inactivate viruses.\n\n===Quaternary ammonium compounds===\n\n[[Quaternary ammonium compounds]] (\"quats\"), such as [[benzalkonium chloride]], are a large group of related compounds. Some concentrated formulations have been shown to be effective low-level disinfectants. Quaternary ammonia at or above 200ppm plus alcohol solutions exhibit efficacy against difficult to kill non-enveloped viruses such as [[norovirus]], [[rotavirus]], or [[polio virus]].<ref name=\"cdc.gov\"/>  Newer synergous, low-alcohol formulations are highly effective broad-spectrum disinfectants with quick contact times (3\u20135 minutes) against bacteria, enveloped viruses, pathogenic fungi, and [[mycobacteria]].  Quats are biocides that also kill algae and are used as an additive in large-scale industrial water systems to minimize undesired biological growth.\n\n=== Inorganic compounds ===\n==== Chlorine ====\nThis group comprises aqueous solution of [[chlorine]], [[hypochlorite]], or [[hypochlorous acid]]. Occasionally, chlorine-releasing compounds and their salts are included in this group. Frequently, a concentration of < 1 ppm of available chlorine is sufficient to kill bacteria and viruses, spores and mycobacteria requiring higher concentrations.\nChlorine has been used for applications, such as the deactivation of pathogens in drinking water, swimming pool water and wastewater, for the disinfection of household areas and for textile bleaching<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lenntech.com/processes/disinfection/chemical/disinfectants-chlorine.htm|title=chlorine as disinfectant for water|website=www.lenntech.com|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref>\n* [[Sodium hypochlorite]]\n* [[Calcium hypochlorite]]\n* [[Monochloramine]]\n* [[Chloramine-T]]\n* [[Trichloroisocyanuric acid]]\n* [[Chlorine dioxide]]\n* [[Hypochlorous acid]]\n\n==== Iodine ====\n* [[Iodine]]\n* [[Iodophor]]s\n==== Acids and bases ====\n* [[Sodium hydroxide]]\n* [[Potassium hydroxide]]\n* [[Calcium hydroxide]]\n* [[Magnesium hydroxide]]\n* [[Sulfurous acid]]\n* [[Sulfur dioxide]]\n====Metals====\n{{main|Oligodynamic effect}}\n\n=== Terpenes ===\n* [[Thymol]]\n* [[Pine oil]]\n\n===Other===\nThe [[biguanide]] [[polymer]] [[polyaminopropyl biguanide]] is specifically bactericidal at very low concentrations (10&nbsp;mg/l). It has a unique method of action: The polymer strands are incorporated into the bacterial cell wall, which disrupts the membrane and reduces its permeability, which has a lethal effect to bacteria. It is also known to bind to bacterial DNA, alter its transcription, and cause lethal DNA damage.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Allen MJ, White GF, Morby AP |title=The response of Escherichia coli to exposure to the biocide polyhexamethylene biguanide |journal=Microbiology |volume=152 |issue=Pt 4 |pages=989\u20131000 |year=2006 |pmid=16549663 |doi=10.1099/mic.0.28643-0 |url=http://mic.sgmjournals.org/cgi/content/full/152/4/989 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526161153/http://mic.sgmjournals.org/cgi/content/full/152/4/989 |archivedate=26 May 2011 |df=dmy-all |doi-access=free }}</ref> It has very low toxicity to higher organisms such as human cells, which have more complex and protective membranes.\n\nCommon [[sodium bicarbonate]] (NaHCO<sub>3</sub>) has antifungal properties,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Zamani M, Sharifi Tehrani A, Ali Abadi AA |title=Evaluation of antifungal activity of carbonate and bicarbonate salts alone or in combination with biocontrol agents in control of citrus green mold |journal=Communications in Agricultural and Applied Biological Sciences |volume=72 |issue=4 |pages=773\u20137 |year=2007 |pmid=18396809}}</ref> and some antiviral and antibacterial properties,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Malik YS, Goyal SM |title=Virucidal efficacy of sodium bicarbonate on a food contact surface against feline calicivirus, a norovirus surrogate |journal=International Journal of Food Microbiology |volume=109 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=160\u20133 |date=May 2006 |pmid=16540196 |doi=10.1016/j.ijfoodmicro.2005.08.033}}</ref> though those are too weak to be effective at a home environment.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=William A. Rutala |author2=Susan L. Barbee |author3=Newman C. Aguiar |author4=Mark D. Sobsey |author5=David J. Weber |year=2000 |title=Antimicrobial Activity of Home Disinfectants and Natural Products Against Potential Human Pathogens |journal=Infection Control and Hospital Epidemiology |volume=21 |issue=1 |pages=33\u201338 |publisher=The University of Chicago Press on behalf of The Society for Healthcare Epidemiology of America |doi=10.1086/501694 |pmid=10656352 |jstor=10}}</ref>\n\n===Non-chemical===\n[[Ultraviolet germicidal irradiation]] is the use of high-intensity shortwave [[ultraviolet light]] for disinfecting smooth surfaces such as dental tools, but not porous materials that are opaque to the light such as wood or foam. Ultraviolet light is also used for municipal [[water treatment]]. Ultraviolet light fixtures are often present in [[microbiology]] labs, and are activated only when there are no occupants in a room (e.g., at night).\n\nHeat treatment can be used for disinfection and sterilization.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://ehs.research.uiowa.edu/87-heat-disinfection-and-sterilization | title = Heat Disinfection and Sterilization | publisher = [[University of Iowa]], Environmental Health & Safety | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170108190620/https://ehs.research.uiowa.edu/87-heat-disinfection-and-sterilization | archivedate = 8 January 2017 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|Sunlight}}The phrase \"sunlight is the best disinfectant\" was [[Other People's Money and How the Bankers Use It|popularized in 1913]] by [[United States Supreme Court]] Justice [[Louis Brandeis]] and later advocates of [[government transparency]]. While sunlight's ultraviolet rays can act as a disinfectant, the Earth's [[ozone layer]] blocks the rays' most effective wavelengths. Ultraviolet light-emitting machines, such as those used to disinfect some hospital rooms, make for better disinfectants than sunlight.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=McCarthy |first1=Ciara |title=Is Sunlight Actually the Best Disinfectant? |work=Slate |date=9 August 2013 |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/explainer/2013/08/sunlight_is_the_best_disinfectant_not_exactly.html |issn=1091-2339 |df=mdy-all |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305042551/http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/explainer/2013/08/sunlight_is_the_best_disinfectant_not_exactly.html |archivedate=5 March 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Measurements of effectiveness==\nOne way to compare disinfectants is to compare how well they do against a known disinfectant and rate them accordingly. Phenol is the standard, and the corresponding rating system is called the \"[[Phenol coefficient]]\". The disinfectant to be tested is compared with phenol on a standard microbe (usually ''[[Salmonella typhi]]'' or ''[[Staphylococcus aureus]]''). Disinfectants that are more effective than phenol have a coefficient &gt; 1. Those that are less effective have a coefficient &lt; 1.\n\nThe standard European approach for disinfectant validation consists of a basic suspension test, a quantitative suspension test (with low and high levels of organic material added to act as \u2018interfering substances\u2019) and a two part simulated-use surface test.<ref name=Sandle>{{cite book | editor = Sandle T | title = The CDC Handbook: A Guide to Cleaning and Disinfecting Cleanrooms  | edition = 1st | publisher = Grosvenor House Publishing Limited | year = 2012 | isbn = 978-1781487686}}</ref>\n\nA less specific measurement of effectiveness is the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) classification into either ''high'', ''intermediate'' or ''low'' levels of disinfection. \"High-level disinfection kills all organisms, except high levels of bacterial spores\" and is done with a chemical germicide marketed as a sterilant by the U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA). \"Intermediate-level disinfection kills mycobacteria, most viruses, and bacteria with a chemical germicide registered as a 'tuberculocide' by the Environmental Protection Agency. Low-level disinfection kills some viruses and bacteria with a chemical germicide registered as a hospital disinfectant by the EPA.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/HAI/prevent/sd_medicalDevices.html |title=Sterilization or Disinfection of Medical Devices |author=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=21 December 2012 |website=CDC |accessdate=20 July 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130720040938/http://www.cdc.gov/HAI/prevent/sd_medicalDevices.html |archivedate=20 July 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAn alternative assessment is to measure the Minimum inhibitory concentrations (MICs) of disinfectants against selected (and representative) microbial species, such as through the use of microbroth dilution testing.<ref>{{Cite journal|vauthors=Vijayakumar R, Kannan VV, Sandle T, Manoharan C\n |title=In vitro Antifungal Efficacy of Biguanides and Quaternary Ammonium Compounds against Cleanroom Fungal Isolates|journal=[[PDA (journal)|PDA J Pharm Sci Technol]] |volume=66 |issue=3 |pages=236\u201342|date=May 2012 |doi=10.5731/pdajpst.2012.00866}}</ref> However, those methods are obtained at standard inoculum levels without considering the inoculum effect. More informative methods are nowadays in demand to determine the minimum disinfectant dose as a function of the density of the target microbial species <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Garc\u00eda|first1=MR|last2=Cabo|first2=ML|title=Optimization of ''E. coli'' Inactivation by Benzalkonium Chloride Reveals the Importance of Quantifying the Inoculum Effect on Chemical Disinfection.|journal=Frontiers in Microbiology|date=June 2018|volume=9|pages=1259|doi=10.3389/fmicb.2018.01259|pmid=29997577|pmc=6028699}}</ref>.\n\n===Health Warning for Human Ingestion, Injection, and Inhalation===\nThe April 23, 2020 [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] meeting addressed by President [[Donald Trump]] included conjecture that injecting or ingesting disinfectants could clean the body from [[coronavirus]] infection. However, this was emphatically denounced by health professionals due to grave danger to the human body.<ref>https://7news.com.au/lifestyle/health-wellbeing/coronavirus-dettol-and-lysol-issue-health-warning-after-donald-trumps-disinfectant-comments-c-998618</ref><ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52411706</ref>\n\n==Home disinfectants==\n{{cleanup|section|reason=Overuse of the definite article, and non-encyclopedic style|date=February 2015}}\n\nThe most cost-effective home disinfectant is [[Bleach|chlorine bleach]] (typically a >10% solution of [[sodium hypochlorite]]), which is effective against most common [[pathogens]], including disinfectant-resistant organisms such as [[tuberculosis]] ([[mycobacterium tuberculosis]]), [[hepatitis]] B and C, [[fungi]], and antibiotic-resistant strains of [[staphylococcus]] and [[enterococcus]]. It has disinfectant action against some [[Parasites|parasitic organisms]].<ref>[http://www.epa.gov/oppad001/chemregindex.htm EPA's Registered Sterilizers, Tuberculocides, and Antimicrobial Products Against [[HIV]]-1, and Hepatitis B and Hepatitis C Viruses.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930061054/http://www.epa.gov/oppad001/chemregindex.htm |date=30 September 2015 }} (Obtained 4 January 2006)</ref>{{Failed verification|date=September 2018}}\n\nThe benefits of chlorine bleach include its inexpensive and fast acting nature. However it is harmful to mucous membranes and skin upon contact, has a strong odour; is not effective against ''[[Giardia lamblia]]'' and ''[[Cryptosporidium]]''; and combination with other cleaning products such as ammonia and [[vinegar]] can generate noxious gases like [[chlorine]]. The best practice is not to add anything to household bleach except water. As with most disinfectants, the area requiring disinfection should be cleaned before the application of the chlorine bleach, as the presence of organic materials may inactivate chlorine bleach.\n\nThe use of some antimicrobials such as [[triclosan]], is controversial because it may lead to [[antimicrobial resistance]]. The use of chlorine bleach and alcohol disinfectants does not cause [[antimicrobial resistance]] as it denatures the protein of the microbe upon contact.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://watoxics.org/healthy-living/healthy-homes-gardens-1/factsheets/antimicrobials |title=Antimicrobial Products: Who Needs Them? \u2014 Washington Toxics Coalition |publisher=Watoxics.org |date=15 September 1997 |accessdate=10 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710230146/http://watoxics.org/healthy-living/healthy-homes-gardens-1/factsheets/antimicrobials |archivedate=10 July 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Drug resistance]]\n* [[Diethylene glycol]] - a raw material for air [[sanitation]]\n* [[Hand sanitizer]]\n* [[Hygiene]]\n* [[List of cleaning products]]\n* [[Sanitation Standard Operating Procedures]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal | title = Virus resistance in a hospital environment: overview of the virucide activity of disinfectants used in liquid form | journal = Annales de Biologie Clinique | date = Nov\u2013Dec 1998 | first = H. | last = Soule |author2=D. L. Duc |author3=M. R. Mallaret |author4=B. Chanzy |author5=A. Charvier |author6=B. Gratacap-Cavallier |author7=P. Morand |author8=J. M. Seigneurin  | volume = 56 | issue = 6 | pages = 693\u2013703 | id =  | language = French | pmid=9853028}}\n*{{cite book | editor = Sandle, T. | title = The CDC Handbook: A Guide to Cleaning and Disinfecting Cleanrooms  | edition = 1st | publisher = Grosvenor House Publishing Limited | year = 2012 | isbn = 978-1781487686}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100724144955/http://www.mansfield.ohio-state.edu/~sabedon/black12.htm Ohio State University lecture on Sterilization and Disinfection]\n* [http://www.unitedsanitizing.com/index.php/technical/frequently-asked-questions/ NAV-CO2 as a disinfection method using Alcohols and Quaternary Ammonia]* \n* [http://www.housekeepingchannel.com/showarticle.php?id=253 What Germs Are We Killing? Testing and Classifying Disinfectants]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090823195546/http://www.bccdc.org/downloads/pdf/epid/reports/CDManual_DisinfectntSelectnGuidelines_sep2003_nov05-03.pdf Disinfectant Selection Guide]\n* [http://www.newton.dep.anl.gov/askasci/chem03/chem03856.htm Disinfectant and Non-Chlorine Bleach]\u2014Office of DOE Science Education\n* [http://www.wien.gv.at/english/environment/protection/oekokauf/disinfectants/index.html The Viennese Database for Disinfectants (WIDES Database)]\n\n{{Antiseptics and disinfectants}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Disinfectants| ]]\n[[Category:Hygiene]]\n[[Category:Bactericides]]\n", "name_user": "2605:a601:ab03:e00:a402:4719:b4e3:986e", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disinfectant"}
{"title_page": "CNCO", "text_new": "{{short description|Latin Boy Band}}\n{{for|the company|The China Navigation Company}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = CNCO\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = CNCO 258 enlarged.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = yes\n| caption          = CNCO debut concert, [[Miami Beach]], January 30, 2016. From left: Joel Pimentel, Erick Brian Col\u00f3n, Richard Camacho, Christopher V\u00e9lez and Zabdiel De Jes\u00fas\n| alias            = \n| origin           = \n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Latin pop]]|[[reggaeton]]}}\n| years_active     = 2015-present\n| label            = [[Sony Music Latin]]\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{URL|cncomusic.com/}}\n| current_members  = * Christopher V\u00e9lez\n* Richard Camacho\n* Zabdiel De Jes\u00fas\n* Joel Pimentel\n* Erick Brian Col\u00f3n\n}}\n\n'''CNCO''' is a Latin American [[boy band]] formed on the first season of ''[[La Banda (TV series)|La Banda]]''.<ref name=\"CNCO\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6806078/cnco-la-banda-boy-band-finale|title=Hello CNCO! 'La Banda' Wraps Season With New Boy Band|last=Cobo|first=Leila|date=December 14, 2015|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref> The group is composed of Joel Pimentel, Richard Camacho, Erick Brian Col\u00f3n, Christopher V\u00e9lez, and Zabdiel De Jes\u00fas. They won a five-year recording contract with [[Sony Music Latin]] after becoming the winning competitors of the first season of ''[[La Banda (TV series)|La Banda]].'' The band toured with [[Ricky Martin]] and their singles. Their debut and second singles \"Tan F\u00e1cil\" and \"Quisiera\", charted well soon after their debut.<ref name=\"charthistory\">{{cite web|title=CNCO \u2013 Billboard chart history|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/6885261/cnco/chart|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"album\">{{cite web|last=Flores|first=Griselda|title=CNCO Tops New Latin Boy Band Reader Poll|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7468401/cnco-new-latin-boy-band-poll|date=August 9, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref> They released their first album, ''[[Primera Cita]]'' on August 26, 2016,<ref name=\"pre-sales\">{{cite web|last=Irizarry|first=Doris|title=CNCO's first album 'Primera Cita' on pre-sale now|url=http://www.axs.com/cnco-s-first-album-primera-cita-on-pre-sale-now-104504|date=August 10, 2016|work=[[AXS TV|AXS]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"release\">{{cite web|last=Civita|first=Alicia|title=CNCO reivindica su autenticidad con su primer disco, \"Primera cita\"|url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/espanol/2016/08/25/cnco-reivindica-su-autenticidad-con-su-primer-disco-primera-cita/|date=August 25, 2016|language=Urdu|work=[[Fox News Channel|Fox News Latino]]|accessdate=August 26, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827125150/http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/espanol/2016/08/25/cnco-reivindica-su-autenticidad-con-su-primer-disco-primera-cita/|archivedate=August 27, 2016}}</ref> which included the hit \"[[Reggaet\u00f3n Lento (Bailemos)]]\".<ref name=\"reggaeton\">{{cite web|last=Cabo|first=Leila|title=Little Mix Team Up With CNCO for 'Reggaeton Lento' Remix|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7905184/little-mix-cnco-reggaeton-lento-remix|date=August 16, 2017|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Raygoza|first=Isabela|title=Best: Introducing CNCO, the K-pop idols of Latin music|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/latin-grammys-2017-luis-fonsi-residente-win-big-w512064/best-introducing-cnco-the-k-pop-idols-of-latin-music-w512083|date=November 17, 2017|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=April 3, 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe group released their [[CNCO (album)|self-titled second album]], on April 6, 2018, which included the singles \"[[Mamita (song)|Mamita]]\" and \"Se Vuelve Loca\".<ref name=\"fresca\">{{cite web|title=CNCO lanza \u00e1lbum con m\u00fasica \"m\u00e1s fresca y madura\"|url=http://www.ecuavisa.com/articulo/entretenimiento/espectaculo/374381-cnco-lanza-album-musica-mas-fresca-madura|date=April 6, 2018|language=Spanish|work=[[Ecuavisa]]|accessdate=April 9, 2018}}</ref> \n\nTheir debut EP ''Que Qui\u00e9nes Somos,'' containing the singles \"De Cero\" and \"Pegao\" featuring [[Manuel Turizo]], was released on August 29.01 Both LPs debuted at number one on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums|''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums]] and the top 40 on th''e [[Billboard 200|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard 200|200]], while the EP debuted within the Top 15 of the former chart.\n\n==History==\n\n=== 2015: ''La Banda'' and \"Devu\u00e9lveme Mi Coraz\u00f3n\" ===\nErick Brian Col\u00f3n, Christopher V\u00e9lez, Zabdiel De Jes\u00fas, Richard Camacho and Joel Pimentel auditioned for the [[La Banda (U.S. season 1)|first season]] of ''La Banda'', a televised singing competition which started on [[Univision]] in September 2015, created by [[Simon Cowell]] and produced by Ricky Martin.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gardner|first=Elysa|title=Ricky Martin joins Simon Cowell's 'La Banda'|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2015/02/19/ricky-martin-to-be-first-judge-on-simon-cowells-la-banda|date=February 19, 2015|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref> They all received an 75% of votes from the public during auditions except Col\u00f3n, though he was saved by Martin. The band's members competed individually with other contestants from [[Latin America]] and the United States before the show's judges, Martin, [[Alejandro Sanz]] and [[Laura Pausini]]. The boys had to go through several phases to become the winners. During the competition, they were put into groups, with Camacho and De Jes\u00fas in the same band, while V\u00e9lez, Col\u00f3n and Pimentel were in another. The band was formed on the finale of the show, on December 13, 2015, when they received their name, which alludes to the Spanish word for five, \"cinco\", and is pronounced in English as it is spelled: \"C-N-C-O.\"<ref name=\"handpicked\">{{cite web|last=Flores|first=Griselda|title=Magneto, CNCO or Menudo? Vote for Your All-Time Favorite Latin Boy Band!|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7439041/magneto-cnco-menudo-latin-boy-band-poll|date=July 15, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref> They won a recording contract of 5 years with [[Sony Music Latin]],<ref name=\"album\"/> and rapper [[Wisin]] was scheduled to produce their first album.<ref name=\"CNCO\" /> Martin became their representative.<ref name=\"pre-sales\"/><ref name=\"winners\">{{cite web|last=Irizarry|first=Doris|title=First 'La Banda' winners form CNCO: the newest Latin boy band|url=http://www.axs.com/first-la-banda-winners-form-cnco-the-newest-latin-boy-band-72399|date=December 16, 2016|work=[[AXS TV|AXS]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThey performed the song \"Devu\u00e9lveme Mi Coraz\u00f3n\" on the finale, which included performances by [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]], [[Fifth Harmony]], Wisin, and a video congratulations from [[One Direction]].<ref name=\"CNCO\" /><ref name=\"winners\"/> They sang it again in [[Times Square]] at Univision's Feliz 2016 [[New Year]]'s celebration.<ref name=\"newyear\">{{cite web|last=Benjamin|first=Jeff|title=Can CNCO Be the Next Big Boy Band? Listen to Debut Single 'Tan F\u00e1cil'|url=http://www..tv/2016/01/cnco-tan-facil-next-big-boy-band|date=January 29, 2016|work=[[Fuse (TV channel)|Fuse TV]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Roiz|first=Jessica Lucia|title=Demi Lovato, Maluma, CNCO, Taylor Swift, Celebrate New Year's Eve In Times Square, Plus Full Performers List|url=http://www.latintimes.com/pulse/demi-lovato-maluma-cnco-taylor-swift-celebrate-new-years-eve-times-square-plus-full-362086|date=December 29, 2015|work=[[IBT Media|Latin Times]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:CNCO (Premio lo Nuestro) 2016 cropped 2.jpg|thumb|CNCO at Univision's [[Premio Lo Nuestro 2016]]]]\n\n===2016: Ricky Martin One World Tour and ''Primera Cita''===\nOn January 29, 2016, they released their debut single, \"Tan F\u00e1cil\"<ref name=\"releasedfirst\">{{cite web|title=Tan F\u00e1cil|url=https://www.amazon.com/Tan-F%C3%A1cil-CNCO/dp/B01AXGH8MI/ref=sr_1_4?s=dmusic&ie=UTF8&qid=1471474103&sr=1-4-mp3-albums-bar-strip-0&keywords=CNCO|date=|work=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref> which debuted on [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']]'s Latin Rhythm Airplay at number 25,<ref name=\"hotlatin\">{{cite web|last=Billboard Staff|title=Tomorrow's Hits: Brandy Clark, CNCO & Gryffin|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6866897/brandy-clark-cnco-gryffin-tomorrows-hits|date=February 5, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref> number 23 on the Hot Latin Songs chart,<ref>{{cite web|last=Fernandez|first=Suzette|title=Latin Notas: CNCO, Jencarlos Canela, Thal\u00eda, Carlos Vives & More|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/6859357/latin-notas-cnco-jencarlos-canela-thalia-carlos-vives-more|date=January 29, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref> and instantly topped the U.S. [[iTunes]] [[Latino (demonym)|Latino]] charts, later peaking at number one on the Latin Airplay chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Latin Airplay chart \u2013 May 14, 2016|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/6885261/cnco/chart?f=1225|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"yankee\">{{cite web|last=Balzano|first=Caterina|title=CNCO ready to take home awards|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/entertainment/celebrities/article89160167.html|date=July 12, 2016|work=[[Miami Herald]]|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref> On January 30, 2016, they held their first concert in [[Miami Beach Convention Center|The Fillmore Miami Beach]].<ref name=\"debuta\">{{cite web|title=CNCO debuta con un concierto en el Fillmore Miami Beach |url=https://www.msn.com/es-us/noticias/otras/cnco-debuta-con-un-concierto-en-el-fillmore-miami-beach/vi-BBoUV6Z?refvid=BBoUV6Z|date=January 30, 2016|language=Spanish|work=[[MSN|Noticias MSN Latino]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"grupo\">{{cite web|title=Grupo CNCO debuta en los escenarios con concierto en el Fillmore Miami Beach|url=http://www.elnuevoherald.com/entretenimiento/musica/article57581003.html|work=[[El Nuevo Herald]]|date=|language=Spanish|accessdate=August 30, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"concierto\">{{cite web|title=Grupo CNCO debuta en los escenarios con concierto en el Fillmore Miami Beach|url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/espanol/2016/01/30/grupo-cnco-debuta-en-los-escenarios-con-concierto-en-el-fillmore-miami-beach/|date=January 30, 2016|language=Spanish|work=[[Fox News Channel|Fox News Latino]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407044813/http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/espanol/2016/01/30/grupo-cnco-debuta-en-los-escenarios-con-concierto-en-el-fillmore-miami-beach/|archivedate=April 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn February 12, CNCO started touring as opening acts on Ricky Martin's [[One World Tour (Ricky Martin)|One World Tour]] for some of his shows in the U.S., including [[Hollywood, Florida]]<ref name=\"HardRock\">{{cite web|last=Sandberg|first=Michele Eve|title=Ricky Martin and CNCO at Hard Rock Live|url=http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/slideshow/ricky-martin-and-cnco-at-hard-rock-live-8039323|date=August 29, 2016|work=[[New Times Broward-Palm Beach]]|accessdate=August 30, 2016}}</ref> [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], and parts of South America, including [[Chile]] and [[Argentina]].<ref name=\"martintour\">{{cite web|last=Billboard Staff|title='La Banda' Winners CNCO to Join Ricky Martin on Tour|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6851599/la-banda-cnco-ricky-martin-tour|date=January 22, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, they released their second single \"Quisiera\",<ref name=\"releasedsecond\">{{cite web|title=Quisiera|url=https://www.amazon.com/Quisiera-CNCO/dp/B01F8O8A5E/ref=sr_1_2?s=dmusic&ie=UTF8&qid=1471474103&sr=1-2-mp3-albums-bar-strip-0&keywords=CNCO|work=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref> which peaked on ''Billboard''<nowiki/>'s Hot Latin Songs at number 29,<ref name=\"album\" /> with its music video premiering on June 3.<ref name=\"secondmv\">{{cite web|title=CNCO estrena su nuevo video \"QUISIERA\"|url=http://www.sonymusiclatin.com/2016/06/04/cnco-estrena-su-nuevo-video-quisiera/|work=[[Sony Music Latin]]|date=June 4, 2016|language=Spanish|accessdate=July 15, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822064224/http://www.sonymusiclatin.com/2016/06/04/cnco-estrena-su-nuevo-video-quisiera/|archivedate=August 22, 2016}}</ref> In May, they sang the [[The Star-Spangled Banner|national anthem]] at [[Yankee Stadium]].<ref name=\"yankee\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=CNCO cant\u00f3 en el estadio de los Yankees |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nkaemBi5lD8|date=May 25, 2016|language=Spanish|work=[[Univision]]/[[YouTube]]|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref> On July 13, the band was nominated for six awards,<ref name=\"yankee\" /> at [[Premios Juventud]] and won five for the Most \u2013 \"Tan F\u00e1cil\", My Pop/Rock Artist Producers' Choice Award, My Favorite Twitter Celebrity, and My Favorite Fan-Army; they also performed at the ceremony.<ref name=\"premios\">{{cite web|last=Flores|first=Griselda|title=Premios Juventud 2016: CNCO, Nicky Jam, Marc Anthony & More Winners |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7438935/premios-juventud-2016-winners|date=July 14, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Raquel Miserachi and Beatriz Vernon|title=The 5 most epic performances of Premios Juventud 2016 |url=http://www.univision.com/musica/throwback/the-5-most-epic-performances-of-premios-juventud-2016|date=July 15, 2016|work=[[Univision]]|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August, their fans, called \"CNCOwners\", voted the band first place in [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']]'s \"Favorite New Latin Boy Band Poll'.<ref name=\"album\" /> On August 23, the group asked fans to locate hotspots for songs from their upcoming album, in a [[Pok\u00e9mon Go]] inspired game, called 'CNCOGo', and [[Ecuador]]ian fans found the first song, \"Cometa\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Flores|first=Griselda|title=CNCO Invites Fans to Play 'CNCOGo' & Catch Their New Songs|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7487012/cnco-cncogo-catch-new-songs-pokemon|date=August 24, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn August 26, their first album, ''[[Primera Cita]]'', (''First Date'', in English), produced by Wisin, was released.<ref name=\"pre-sales\" /><ref name=\"release\" /><ref name=\"fanmeet\">{{cite web|last=Correa|first=Adriana|title=Latin Boy Band CNCO Celebrates Album Debut with Fans in Miami|url=http://www.nbcmiami.com/news/local/Latin-Boy-Band-CNCO-Celebrates-Album-Debut-with-Fans-in-Miami-391547801.html|date=August 28, 2016|work=[[WTVJ]]|accessdate=August 30, 2016}}</ref> Wisin spoke about their album saying, \"It is a union of countries and cultures. It is what keeps us growing because the people can understand that we can unite different genres.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Contreras|first=Milly|title=Nicky Jam Releases Video, Daddy Yankee Hits No 1, Wisin Talks CNCO|url=http://www.latinpost.com/articles/109121/20160115/reggaeton-news-nicky-jams-new-video-daddy-yankees-number-one-single-wisin-talks-cnco.htm|date=January 15, 2016|work=Latin Post|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref> The album has fourteen tracks and includes an urban remix of \"Tan F\u00e1cil\" featuring the rapper, and a ballad version of the song \"Quisiera\" featuring Spanish singer [[Abraham Mateo]].<ref name=\"fanmeet\" /><ref name=\"tracklisting\">{{cite web|last=|first=|title=Primera Cita \u2013 CNCO|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/primera-cita/id1139444702|date=August 26, 2016|work=[[iTunes]]|accessdate=August 30, 2016}}</ref> On its release date, the band met fans while traveling with [[Ricky Martin]] on his tour, and they gave a concert at the [[Miami International Mall]] to celebrate the album's debut.<ref name=\"HardRock\" /><ref name=\"fanmeet\" /><ref>{{cite web|last=Marr|first=Madeleine|title='La Banda' winners, Latin boy band CNCO, at Macy's |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/entertainment/celebrities/article97607552.html|date=August 24, 2016|work=[[Miami Herald]]|accessdate=August 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November, they filmed a new music video for one of the songs on ''Primera Cita'', \"Para Enamorarte\", at the Los Angeles [[Ramon C. Cortines School of Visual and Performing Arts]]. It was produced in conjunction with [[Toyota]] and included fans who also selected the ending of the video. A video clip was scheduled for airing on ''La Banda's'' season finale on December 11, then on Toyota's Latino Facebook page and on YouTube. They also announced plans for their first headlining tour in February 2017 in Latin America.<ref name=\"filming\">{{cite web|last=Flores|first=Griselda|title=CNCO Talks New Music Video 'Para Enamorarte,' Plus Exclusive Photos From Shoot in L.A. |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7595869/cnco-interview-new-music-video-para-enamorarte|date=November 30, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref> On October 7, they released the single \"[[Reggaet\u00f3n Lento (Bailemos)]]\", which peaked at number 6 on the ''Billboard'' Hot Latin Songs chart and number 11 on the [[Billboard Bubbling Under Hot 100 Singles|Bubbling Under Hot 100]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/cnco/chart-history/latin-songs/song/992070|title=CNCO \u2013 Chart History \u2013 Hot Latin Songs|date=April 8, 2017|website=Billboard|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u20132018: ''M\u00e1s All\u00e1'' Tour and ''CNCO'' World Tour===\nOn February 7, 2017, the band was announced as one of four finalists in the category \"Artist of the Year, New\" for the 2017 ''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards, representing artists who charted well over the past year.<ref name=\"finalists\">{{cite web|last=Mendizabal|first=Amaya|title=Meet the Finalists for Artist of the Year, New, for the 2017 Billboard Latin Music Awards|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7684925/billboard-latin-music-awards-best-new-artist-finalists|date=February 7, 2017|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=February 7, 2017}}</ref> On February 26 they began their first headlining tour, M\u00e1s All\u00e1, in [[Cochabamba]], Bolivia, for a total of 15 countries, including 40 performances in Central and South America, Mexico, Portugal, Spain, and the United States;<ref name=\"finalists\"/><ref name=\"tour dates\">{{cite web|last=Irizarry|first=Doris|title=CNCO to kick off first worldwide tour|url=http://www.axs.com/cnco-to-kick-off-first-worldwide-tour-114067|date=February 3, 2017|work=[[AXS TV|AXS]]|accessdate=February 7, 2017}}</ref> and recorded music for their second album while on tour.<ref name=\"fresca\"/>\n\nOn April 4, 2017, the group officially released the lead single from their second album, \"[[Hey DJ (CNCO song)|Hey DJ]]\", featuring Puerto Rican singer [[Yandel]]; they also released a solo pop version. On August 18, CNCO released a [[Reggaet\u00f3n Lento (Bailemos)#Little Mix remix|remixed version]] of \"Reggaet\u00f3n Lento\" featuring vocals from British girl group [[Little Mix]] as the second single from the record. On October 20, 2017, the group released the third single, \"[[Mamita (song)|Mamita]]\" from their second album. On March 3, 2018, they released the song, \"Mi Medicina,\" announcing the album's pre-order.<ref>{{cite web|title=CNCO tiene 'Mi medicina' y la tuya tambi\u00e9n|url=http://www.billboard.com.ar/noticia/4754/cnco-tiene-mi-medicina-y-la-tuya-tambin|date=March 2, 2018|language=Spanish|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard Argentina]]|accessdate=April 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407120116/http://www.billboard.com.ar/noticia/4754/cnco-tiene-mi-medicina-y-la-tuya-tambin|archive-date=April 7, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8220945/cnco-release-date-second-album|title=CNCO Reveal Release Date for Self-Titled Sophomore Album|work=Billboard|last=Fernandez|first=Suzette|date=February 26, 2018|accessdate=March 8, 2018}}</ref> It was followed by \"Bonita\" two weeks later, on March 16, and finally \"Fiesta en Mi Casa\", also arriving two weeks later, on March 30. The music videos accompanied the songs' releases.\n\nOn April 6, 2018, the boy band released their highly anticipated second self-titled album, ''[[CNCO (album)|CNCO]]''.<ref name=\"fresca\"/> It debuted at number one on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums|''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums]] and entered at number 33 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], succeeding their debut. The group released \"S\u00f3lo Yo\", along with its music video, to celebrate the album's release. The music video for the fifth single \"Se Vuelve Loca\" was made available on July 19, with a Spanglish version being released for digital download and streaming several hours later. It reached number one on the Latin Pop Songs Chart in October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8480828/cnco-se-vuelve-loca-latin-pop-songs-chart|title=CNCO's 'Se Vuelve Loca' Hits No. 1 on Latin Pop Songs Chart|last=Bustios|first=Pamela|date=October 19, 2018|website=Billboard|accessdate=November 8, 2018}}</ref> The band embarked on the CNCO World Tour, starting in Guatemala. They announced shows in the United States, thus becoming their first U.S. tour. The band released a collaboration with singer-songwriter [[Prince Royce]] on October 26, titled \"Llegaste T\u00fa\". On November 8, the group released a [[Hey DJ (CNCO song)#Meghan Trainor and Sean Paul remix|remix version]] of \"Hey DJ\", with American singer-songwriter [[Meghan Trainor]] and Jamaican artist [[Sean Paul]].\n\nOn May 16, 2018, CNCO signed a new management deal with Walter Kolm Entertainment, after being managed by Ricky Martin for nearly three years. Walter Kolm Entertainment has also signed other successful artists like [[Maluma (singer)|Maluma]], [[Wisin]], and [[Silvestre Dangond]].\n\n===2019-present: ''Que Quienes Somos''===\nThe band announced the single \"Pretend\", which was released on February 15, 2019. The song is their first official solo Spanglish release, and samples \"[[Rhythm of the Night (song)|Rhythm of the Night]]\" by [[DeBarge]].\n\nCNCO released the single \"De Cero\" on June 24 along with its music video. They performed a short version of \"Pretend\" at the [[2019 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards of 2019]], where they won the Choice Latin Artist and were nominated for Choice Group. Spanish singer-songwriter Abraham Mateo launched his song \"Me Vuelvo Loco\" in collaboration with the boys in July. The group revealed their first extended play, ''Que Qui\u00e9nes Somos'', in mid-August, along with its cover art. Its title references the line sung by Col\u00f3n at the end in most of their songs and also alludes as to who the boys are as they co-wrote the EP themselves. They released the first promotional single, titled \"Ya T\u00fa Sabes\" in the 23rd of the same month. It contains a sample of a song by Cuban salsa singer, [[Celia Cruz]] and features Latin Trap in its production. The second promotional song, named \"La Ley\", was made free on all digital platforms on September 27. Both songs were released with audios on YouTube. The EP was released on 11 October 2019 and includes seven tracks in total. They also released the single \"Pegao\" with [[Manuel Turizo]] on the same day with a music video. The EP ''Que Qui\u00e9nes Somos'' debuted at #1 on the Latin Pop Albums ''Billboard'' chart. The group collaborated with fellow boy band [[PRETTYMUCH]] on the song \"Me Necesita.\" CNCO performed \"Ya T\u00fa Sabes\" and also performed \"Me Vuelvo Loco\" alongside [[Abraham Mateo]] at the 2019 Latin American Music Awards and also won 2 awards that night. On November 7th the group was featured on the song \"[[Como As\u00ed]]\" by Argentinian singer [[Lali Esp\u00f3sito]], which will appear on her upcoming album. In the same month, CNCO announced a clothing campaign with [[Forever 21]].\n\n=== '''2020: Press Start Tour''' ===\nThe band announced their new tour \"Press Start\" on January 21, 2020. The tour will begin on May 30, 2020 at the [[Jos\u00e9 Miguel Agrelot Coliseum|Coliseo de Puerto Rico]] in San Juan, Puerto Rico. The first leg of the tour will consist of 11 cities. The first leg of the tour will end in Chicago, Illinois at the Rosemont Theater on June 21, 2020.\n<br />\n== Members ==\n\n=== Christopher V\u00e9lez ===\nChristopher Bryant V\u00e9lez Mu\u00f1oz was born on November 23, 1995 in [[New Jersey]]. He moved with his family to their home country, Ecuador when he was three years old. When he turned 18, V\u00e9lez returned to the U.S. in hopes of helping his family economically; he had several jobs, including shining shoes for a living. He originally wanted to go to school to study music but saw ''La Banda'' as a better opportunity. V\u00e9lez is also the oldest member in CNCO. He is also a recovering sex addict.<ref name=\"winners4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.axs.com/first-la-banda-winners-form-cnco-the-newest-latin-boy-band-72399|title=First 'La Banda' winners form CNCO: the newest Latin boy band|last=Irizarry|first=Doris|date=December 16, 2015|work=[[AXS TV|AXS]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Richard Camacho ===\nRichard Yashel Camacho Puello was born on January 22, 1997, in [[New York City]] and grew up in the [[Dominican Republic]]. His father is a musician and cameraman and his mother is a dancer, which is also a hobby for him. Camacho has been singing and dancing ever since he was just three years old, and the first song he has ever listened to was \"With You\" by [[Chris Brown]]. He has three other siblings; Yashua Camacho, who also took the lifestyle of singing and is a solo artist, Dairan Camacho and Yarliza Camacho. He has a daughter named Aaliyah Sofia Camacho, which he had with Instagram model, Yocelyn Alexander.<ref name=\"winners4\"/>\n\n=== Zabdiel De Jes\u00fas ===\nZabdiel De Jes\u00fas Col\u00f3n was born in [[Bayam\u00f3n, Puerto Rico]] on December 13, 1997. He developed an interest in singing at age twelve, singing with his church [[Hip hop music|hip-hop]] and [[Salsa music|salsa]] group, as well as dancing ballet at Ballet Concierto, a prestigious academy in Puerto Rico. As a young child, his father, a musician, showed him a love for the music that is now what keeps their family together. From a young age, De Jes\u00fas had the ability to play instruments that was incredible and that's where his love for music comes from. He has shown his skills at [[beatboxing]]. Interestingly, De Jes\u00fas' birthday is on the same day as the group's.<ref name=\"CNCO Music\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cncomusic.com/|title=CNCO Music|work=CNCOMusic.com|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Joel Pimentel ===\nJoel Pimentel de Le\u00f3n was born in [[Victorville, California]] on February 28, 1999, but grew up in [[Hesperia, California|Hesperia]]. He has [[Mexican Americans|Mexican]] ancestry and was inspired by his late grandfather to pursue his music career. He was part of the drama club at [[Hesperia High School]], where he discovered his acting skills. In his spare time, Pimentel likes to play soccer, write songs and act. At one point during ''La Banda,'' Pimentel believed he would be eliminated because he couldn't speak or sing in Spanish very well as it was not his first language. However, his talent helped him become a member of CNCO.\n\n=== Erick Brian Col\u00f3n ===\nErick Brian Col\u00f3n Arista was born on January 3, 2001 in [[Havana]], [[Cuba]]. He moved to [[Tampa, Florida]] with his family at the age of 11 in 2012. There, Col\u00f3n played [[soccer]], danced and participated in musical activities at school. Col\u00f3n has a sister named Yanelis. He is the youngest member of the boyband and was in ''La Banda'' when he was just 14 years old.<ref name=\"winners4\" /><ref name=\" CNCO Music\" />\n\n== Reception ==\nGriselda Flores of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' said the band is \"taking the torch and leading a new boy band era\", like prior [[Latino (demonym)|Latino]] bands [[Magneto (band)|Magneto]], [[Menudo (band)|Menudo]], [[Uff!]], and [[:es:Salser\u00edn|Salser\u00edn]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7439041/magneto-cnco-menudo-latin-boy-band-poll|title=Magneto, CNCO or Menudo? Vote for Your All-Time Favorite Latin Boy Band!|last=Flores|first=Griselda|date=July 15, 2016|website=Billboard|accessdate=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{main|CNCO discography}}\n\n'''Studio albums'''\n* ''[[Primera Cita]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[CNCO (album)|CNCO]]'' (2018)\n\n'''Extended plays'''\n* ''Que Qui\u00e9nes Somos'' (2019)\n\n== Concert tours ==\n===Headlining===\n\n*2017: [[Primera Cita#M\u00e1s All\u00e1 Tour|M\u00e1s All\u00e1 Tour]]<ref name=\"finalists\" /><ref name=\"tour dates\" />\n*2018-2019: [[CNCO (album)#CNCO World Tour|CNCO World Tour]]\n* 2020: Press Start Tour<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://substreammagazine.com/2020/01/cnco-press-start-tour-2020/|title=CNCO announce first leg of 2020 \"Press Start\" tour|last=White|first=Logan|date=2020-01-22|website=Substream Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref>\n\n===As opening act===\n* 2016: [[One World Tour (Ricky Martin)|Ricky Martin's One World Tour]]<ref name=\"HardRock\"/><ref name=\"martintour\"/>\n*2017: [[Ariana Grande]] \u2013 [[Dangerous Woman Tour]]\n* 2017: [[Enrique Iglesias And Pitbull Tour]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Flores|first=Griselda|title=Enrique Iglesias, Pitbull & CNCO Kick Off Tour With Sold-Out Concert in Chicago|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7817594/pitbull-enrique-iglesias-cnco-chicago-concert-recap|date=June 4, 2017|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n[[File:CNCO Lo Nuestro 1.jpg|thumb|right|CNCO receiving award at [[Lo Nuestro Awards]] 2017, with Ricky Martin]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category\n!Nominated work\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"10\" |2016\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"7\"|[[Premios Juventud]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Voz del Momento\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"4\"|Themselves\n|{{nominated}}\n|rowspan=\"7\"|<ref name=\"pre-sales\"/><ref name=\"premios\"/>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Mi Artista Pop Rock\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Producers Choice Award\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Mi Tuitero Favorito \n|{{won}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|La Mas Pegajosa\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\"Tan F\u00e1cil\"\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Mi \"Fan Army\" Favorito\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|CNCOwners\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Mejor Look\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Themselves\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"|[[Latin American Music Awards]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Favorite Pop/Rock New Artist\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"|Themselves\n|{{won}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"|<ref name=\"latin\">{{cite web|last=Flores|first=Griselda|title=Latin American Music Awards 2016 Winners: Enrique Iglesias, CNCO & More|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7534122/latin-american-music-awards-2016-winners|date=October 6, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=October 6, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Favorite Pop/Rock Duo or Group\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Xfinitiy New Artist of the Year\n|{{won}}\n|-\n\n| rowspan=\"10\" |2017\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"|[[Lo Nuestro Awards|Premios Lo Nuestro]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Pop/Rock Song of the Year\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\"Tan F\u00e1cil\" \n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"|<ref name=\"PLN17\">{{cite web|last=Flores|first=Griselda|title=Premio Lo Nuestro 2017: See the Full Winners List|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7701901/premio-lo-nuestro-2017-full-winners-list|date=February 23, 2017|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Pop/Rock Album of the Year\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|''[[Primera Cita]]''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Pop/Rock Group or Duo of the Year\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Themselves\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"4\"|[[Billboard Latin Music Awards]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Artist of the Year Debut\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |Themselves\n|{{won}}\n|rowspan=\"4\"|<ref>{{cite web |last= Harrison |first=Lily |title= Billboard Latin Music Awards 2017: Complete List of Winners |url= http://www.eonline.com/news/846511/billboard-latin-music-awards-2017-complete-list-of-winners |date= October 13, 2017 |work= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Latin Pop Songs Artist of the Year, Duo or Group:\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|Latin Pop Album of the Year\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|''Primera Cita'' \n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align