u00fas\n* Joel Pimentel\n* Erick Brian Col\u00f3n\n}}\n\n'''CNCO''' is a Latin American [[boy band]] formed on the first season of ''[[La Banda (TV series)|La Banda]]''.<ref name=\"CNCO\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6806078/cnco-la-banda-boy-band-finale|title=Hello CNCO! 'La Banda' Wraps Season With New Boy Band|last=Cobo|first=Leila|date=December 14, 2015|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref> The group is composed of Joel Pimentel, Richard Camacho, Erick Brian Col\u00f3n, Christopher V\u00e9lez, and Zabdiel De Jes\u00fas. They won a five-year recording contract with [[Sony Music Latin]] after becoming the winning competitors of the first season of ''[[La Banda (TV series)|La Banda]].'' The band toured with [[Ricky Martin]] and their singles. Their debut and second singles \"Tan F\u00e1cil\" and \"Quisiera\", charted well soon after their debut.<ref name=\"charthistory\">{{cite web|title=CNCO \u2013 Billboard chart history|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/6885261/cnco/chart|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"album\">{{cite web|last=Flores|first=Griselda|title=CNCO Tops New Latin Boy Band Reader Poll|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7468401/cnco-new-latin-boy-band-poll|date=August 9, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref> They released their first album, ''[[Primera Cita]]'' on August 26, 2016,<ref name=\"pre-sales\">{{cite web|last=Irizarry|first=Doris|title=CNCO's first album 'Primera Cita' on pre-sale now|url=http://www.axs.com/cnco-s-first-album-primera-cita-on-pre-sale-now-104504|date=August 10, 2016|work=[[AXS TV|AXS]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"release\">{{cite web|last=Civita|first=Alicia|title=CNCO reivindica su autenticidad con su primer disco, \"Primera cita\"|url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/espanol/2016/08/25/cnco-reivindica-su-autenticidad-con-su-primer-disco-primera-cita/|date=August 25, 2016|language=Urdu|work=[[Fox News Channel|Fox News Latino]]|accessdate=August 26, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827125150/http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/espanol/2016/08/25/cnco-reivindica-su-autenticidad-con-su-primer-disco-primera-cita/|archivedate=August 27, 2016}}</ref> which included the hit \"[[Reggaet\u00f3n Lento (Bailemos)]]\".<ref name=\"reggaeton\">{{cite web|last=Cabo|first=Leila|title=Little Mix Team Up With CNCO for 'Reggaeton Lento' Remix|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7905184/little-mix-cnco-reggaeton-lento-remix|date=August 16, 2017|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Raygoza|first=Isabela|title=Best: Introducing CNCO, the K-pop idols of Latin music|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/latin-grammys-2017-luis-fonsi-residente-win-big-w512064/best-introducing-cnco-the-k-pop-idols-of-latin-music-w512083|date=November 17, 2017|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=April 3, 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe group released their [[CNCO (album)|self-titled second album]], on April 6, 2018, which included the singles \"[[Mamita (song)|Mamita]]\" and \"Se Vuelve Loca\".<ref name=\"fresca\">{{cite web|title=CNCO lanza \u00e1lbum con m\u00fasica \"m\u00e1s fresca y madura\"|url=http://www.ecuavisa.com/articulo/entretenimiento/espectaculo/374381-cnco-lanza-album-musica-mas-fresca-madura|date=April 6, 2018|language=Spanish|work=[[Ecuavisa]]|accessdate=April 9, 2018}}</ref> \n\nTheir debut EP ''Que Qui\u00e9nes Somos,'' containing the singles \"De Cero\" and \"Pegao\" featuring [[Manuel Turizo]], was released on August 29.01 Both LPs debuted at number one on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums|''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums]] and the top 40 on th''e [[Billboard 200|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard 200|200]], while the EP debuted within the Top 15 of the former chart.\n\n==History==\n\n=== 2015: ''La Banda'' and \"Devu\u00e9lveme Mi Coraz\u00f3n\" ===\nErick Brian Col\u00f3n, Christopher V\u00e9lez, Zabdiel De Jes\u00fas, Richard Camacho and Joel Pimentel auditioned for the [[La Banda (U.S. season 1)|first season]] of ''La Banda'', a televised singing competition which started on [[Univision]] in September 2015, created by [[Simon Cowell]] and produced by Ricky Martin.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gardner|first=Elysa|title=Ricky Martin joins Simon Cowell's 'La Banda'|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2015/02/19/ricky-martin-to-be-first-judge-on-simon-cowells-la-banda|date=February 19, 2015|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref> They all received an 75% of votes from the public during auditions except Col\u00f3n, though he was saved by Martin. The band's members competed individually with other contestants from [[Latin America]] and the United States before the show's judges, Martin, [[Alejandro Sanz]] and [[Laura Pausini]]. The boys had to go through several phases to become the winners. During the competition, they were put into groups, with Camacho and De Jes\u00fas in the same band, while V\u00e9lez, Col\u00f3n and Pimentel were in another. The band was formed on the finale of the show, on December 13, 2015, when they received their name, which alludes to the Spanish word for five, \"cinco\", and is pronounced in English as it is spelled: \"C-N-C-O.\"<ref name=\"handpicked\">{{cite web|last=Flores|first=Griselda|title=Magneto, CNCO or Menudo? Vote for Your All-Time Favorite Latin Boy Band!|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7439041/magneto-cnco-menudo-latin-boy-band-poll|date=July 15, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref> They won a recording contract of 5 years with [[Sony Music Latin]],<ref name=\"album\"/> and rapper [[Wisin]] was scheduled to produce their first album.<ref name=\"CNCO\" /> Martin became their representative.<ref name=\"pre-sales\"/><ref name=\"winners\">{{cite web|last=Irizarry|first=Doris|title=First 'La Banda' winners form CNCO: the newest Latin boy band|url=http://www.axs.com/first-la-banda-winners-form-cnco-the-newest-latin-boy-band-72399|date=December 16, 2016|work=[[AXS TV|AXS]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThey performed the song \"Devu\u00e9lveme Mi Coraz\u00f3n\" on the finale, which included performances by [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]], [[Fifth Harmony]], Wisin, and a video congratulations from [[One Direction]].<ref name=\"CNCO\" /><ref name=\"winners\"/> They sang it again in [[Times Square]] at Univision's Feliz 2016 [[New Year]]'s celebration.<ref name=\"newyear\">{{cite web|last=Benjamin|first=Jeff|title=Can CNCO Be the Next Big Boy Band? Listen to Debut Single 'Tan F\u00e1cil'|url=http://www..tv/2016/01/cnco-tan-facil-next-big-boy-band|date=January 29, 2016|work=[[Fuse (TV channel)|Fuse TV]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Roiz|first=Jessica Lucia|title=Demi Lovato, Maluma, CNCO, Taylor Swift, Celebrate New Year's Eve In Times Square, Plus Full Performers List|url=http://www.latintimes.com/pulse/demi-lovato-maluma-cnco-taylor-swift-celebrate-new-years-eve-times-square-plus-full-362086|date=December 29, 2015|work=[[IBT Media|Latin Times]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:CNCO (Premio lo Nuestro) 2016 cropped 2.jpg|thumb|CNCO at Univision's [[Premio Lo Nuestro 2016]]]]\n\n===2016: Ricky Martin One World Tour and ''Primera Cita''===\nOn January 29, 2016, they released their debut single, \"Tan F\u00e1cil\"<ref name=\"releasedfirst\">{{cite web|title=Tan F\u00e1cil|url=https://www.amazon.com/Tan-F%C3%A1cil-CNCO/dp/B01AXGH8MI/ref=sr_1_4?s=dmusic&ie=UTF8&qid=1471474103&sr=1-4-mp3-albums-bar-strip-0&keywords=CNCO|date=|work=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref> which debuted on [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']]'s Latin Rhythm Airplay at number 25,<ref name=\"hotlatin\">{{cite web|last=Billboard Staff|title=Tomorrow's Hits: Brandy Clark, CNCO & Gryffin|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6866897/brandy-clark-cnco-gryffin-tomorrows-hits|date=February 5, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref> number 23 on the Hot Latin Songs chart,<ref>{{cite web|last=Fernandez|first=Suzette|title=Latin Notas: CNCO, Jencarlos Canela, Thal\u00eda, Carlos Vives & More|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/6859357/latin-notas-cnco-jencarlos-canela-thalia-carlos-vives-more|date=January 29, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref> and instantly topped the U.S. [[iTunes]] [[Latino (demonym)|Latino]] charts, later peaking at number one on the Latin Airplay chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Latin Airplay chart \u2013 May 14, 2016|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/6885261/cnco/chart?f=1225|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"yankee\">{{cite web|last=Balzano|first=Caterina|title=CNCO ready to take home awards|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/entertainment/celebrities/article89160167.html|date=July 12, 2016|work=[[Miami Herald]]|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref> On January 30, 2016, they held their first concert in [[Miami Beach Convention Center|The Fillmore Miami Beach]].<ref name=\"debuta\">{{cite web|title=CNCO debuta con un concierto en el Fillmore Miami Beach |url=https://www.msn.com/es-us/noticias/otras/cnco-debuta-con-un-concierto-en-el-fillmore-miami-beach/vi-BBoUV6Z?refvid=BBoUV6Z|date=January 30, 2016|language=Spanish|work=[[MSN|Noticias MSN Latino]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"grupo\">{{cite web|title=Grupo CNCO debuta en los escenarios con concierto en el Fillmore Miami Beach|url=http://www.elnuevoherald.com/entretenimiento/musica/article57581003.html|work=[[El Nuevo Herald]]|date=|language=Spanish|accessdate=August 30, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"concierto\">{{cite web|title=Grupo CNCO debuta en los escenarios con concierto en el Fillmore Miami Beach|url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/espanol/2016/01/30/grupo-cnco-debuta-en-los-escenarios-con-concierto-en-el-fillmore-miami-beach/|date=January 30, 2016|language=Spanish|work=[[Fox News Channel|Fox News Latino]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407044813/http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/espanol/2016/01/30/grupo-cnco-debuta-en-los-escenarios-con-concierto-en-el-fillmore-miami-beach/|archivedate=April 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn February 12, CNCO started touring as opening acts on Ricky Martin's [[One World Tour (Ricky Martin)|One World Tour]] for some of his shows in the U.S., including [[Hollywood, Florida]]<ref name=\"HardRock\">{{cite web|last=Sandberg|first=Michele Eve|title=Ricky Martin and CNCO at Hard Rock Live|url=http://www.browardpalmbeach.com/slideshow/ricky-martin-and-cnco-at-hard-rock-live-8039323|date=August 29, 2016|work=[[New Times Broward-Palm Beach]]|accessdate=August 30, 2016}}</ref> [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], and parts of South America, including [[Chile]] and [[Argentina]].<ref name=\"martintour\">{{cite web|last=Billboard Staff|title='La Banda' Winners CNCO to Join Ricky Martin on Tour|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6851599/la-banda-cnco-ricky-martin-tour|date=January 22, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, they released their second single \"Quisiera\",<ref name=\"releasedsecond\">{{cite web|title=Quisiera|url=https://www.amazon.com/Quisiera-CNCO/dp/B01F8O8A5E/ref=sr_1_2?s=dmusic&ie=UTF8&qid=1471474103&sr=1-2-mp3-albums-bar-strip-0&keywords=CNCO|work=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref> which peaked on ''Billboard''<nowiki/>'s Hot Latin Songs at number 29,<ref name=\"album\" /> with its music video premiering on June 3.<ref name=\"secondmv\">{{cite web|title=CNCO estrena su nuevo video \"QUISIERA\"|url=http://www.sonymusiclatin.com/2016/06/04/cnco-estrena-su-nuevo-video-quisiera/|work=[[Sony Music Latin]]|date=June 4, 2016|language=Spanish|accessdate=July 15, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822064224/http://www.sonymusiclatin.com/2016/06/04/cnco-estrena-su-nuevo-video-quisiera/|archivedate=August 22, 2016}}</ref> In May, they sang the [[The Star-Spangled Banner|national anthem]] at [[Yankee Stadium]].<ref name=\"yankee\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=CNCO cant\u00f3 en el estadio de los Yankees |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nkaemBi5lD8|date=May 25, 2016|language=Spanish|work=[[Univision]]/[[YouTube]]|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref> On July 13, the band was nominated for six awards,<ref name=\"yankee\" /> at [[Premios Juventud]] and won five for the Most \u2013 \"Tan F\u00e1cil\", My Pop/Rock Artist Producers' Choice Award, My Favorite Twitter Celebrity, and My Favorite Fan-Army; they also performed at the ceremony.<ref name=\"premios\">{{cite web|last=Flores|first=Griselda|title=Premios Juventud 2016: CNCO, Nicky Jam, Marc Anthony & More Winners |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7438935/premios-juventud-2016-winners|date=July 14, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Raquel Miserachi and Beatriz Vernon|title=The 5 most epic performances of Premios Juventud 2016 |url=http://www.univision.com/musica/throwback/the-5-most-epic-performances-of-premios-juventud-2016|date=July 15, 2016|work=[[Univision]]|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August, their fans, called \"CNCOwners\", voted the band first place in [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']]'s \"Favorite New Latin Boy Band Poll'.<ref name=\"album\" /> On August 23, the group asked fans to locate hotspots for songs from their upcoming album, in a [[Pok\u00e9mon Go]] inspired game, called 'CNCOGo', and [[Ecuador]]ian fans found the first song, \"Cometa\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Flores|first=Griselda|title=CNCO Invites Fans to Play 'CNCOGo' & Catch Their New Songs|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7487012/cnco-cncogo-catch-new-songs-pokemon|date=August 24, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn August 26, their first album, ''[[Primera Cita]]'', (''First Date'', in English), produced by Wisin, was released.<ref name=\"pre-sales\" /><ref name=\"release\" /><ref name=\"fanmeet\">{{cite web|last=Correa|first=Adriana|title=Latin Boy Band CNCO Celebrates Album Debut with Fans in Miami|url=http://www.nbcmiami.com/news/local/Latin-Boy-Band-CNCO-Celebrates-Album-Debut-with-Fans-in-Miami-391547801.html|date=August 28, 2016|work=[[WTVJ]]|accessdate=August 30, 2016}}</ref> Wisin spoke about their album saying, \"It is a union of countries and cultures. It is what keeps us growing because the people can understand that we can unite different genres.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Contreras|first=Milly|title=Nicky Jam Releases Video, Daddy Yankee Hits No 1, Wisin Talks CNCO|url=http://www.latinpost.com/articles/109121/20160115/reggaeton-news-nicky-jams-new-video-daddy-yankees-number-one-single-wisin-talks-cnco.htm|date=January 15, 2016|work=Latin Post|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref> The album has fourteen tracks and includes an urban remix of \"Tan F\u00e1cil\" featuring the rapper, and a ballad version of the song \"Quisiera\" featuring Spanish singer [[Abraham Mateo]].<ref name=\"fanmeet\" /><ref name=\"tracklisting\">{{cite web|last=|first=|title=Primera Cita \u2013 CNCO|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/primera-cita/id1139444702|date=August 26, 2016|work=[[iTunes]]|accessdate=August 30, 2016}}</ref> On its release date, the band met fans while traveling with [[Ricky Martin]] on his tour, and they gave a concert at the [[Miami International Mall]] to celebrate the album's debut.<ref name=\"HardRock\" /><ref name=\"fanmeet\" /><ref>{{cite web|last=Marr|first=Madeleine|title='La Banda' winners, Latin boy band CNCO, at Macy's |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/entertainment/celebrities/article97607552.html|date=August 24, 2016|work=[[Miami Herald]]|accessdate=August 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November, they filmed a new music video for one of the songs on ''Primera Cita'', \"Para Enamorarte\", at the Los Angeles [[Ramon C. Cortines School of Visual and Performing Arts]]. It was produced in conjunction with [[Toyota]] and included fans who also selected the ending of the video. A video clip was scheduled for airing on ''La Banda's'' season finale on December 11, then on Toyota's Latino Facebook page and on YouTube. They also announced plans for their first headlining tour in February 2017 in Latin America.<ref name=\"filming\">{{cite web|last=Flores|first=Griselda|title=CNCO Talks New Music Video 'Para Enamorarte,' Plus Exclusive Photos From Shoot in L.A. |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7595869/cnco-interview-new-music-video-para-enamorarte|date=November 30, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref> On October 7, they released the single \"[[Reggaet\u00f3n Lento (Bailemos)]]\", which peaked at number 6 on the ''Billboard'' Hot Latin Songs chart and number 11 on the [[Billboard Bubbling Under Hot 100 Singles|Bubbling Under Hot 100]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/cnco/chart-history/latin-songs/song/992070|title=CNCO \u2013 Chart History \u2013 Hot Latin Songs|date=April 8, 2017|website=Billboard|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u20132018: ''M\u00e1s All\u00e1'' Tour and ''CNCO'' World Tour===\nOn February 7, 2017, the band was announced as one of four finalists in the category \"Artist of the Year, New\" for the 2017 ''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards, representing artists who charted well over the past year.<ref name=\"finalists\">{{cite web|last=Mendizabal|first=Amaya|title=Meet the Finalists for Artist of the Year, New, for the 2017 Billboard Latin Music Awards|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7684925/billboard-latin-music-awards-best-new-artist-finalists|date=February 7, 2017|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=February 7, 2017}}</ref> On February 26 they began their first headlining tour, M\u00e1s All\u00e1, in [[Cochabamba]], Bolivia, for a total of 15 countries, including 40 performances in Central and South America, Mexico, Portugal, Spain, and the United States;<ref name=\"finalists\"/><ref name=\"tour dates\">{{cite web|last=Irizarry|first=Doris|title=CNCO to kick off first worldwide tour|url=http://www.axs.com/cnco-to-kick-off-first-worldwide-tour-114067|date=February 3, 2017|work=[[AXS TV|AXS]]|accessdate=February 7, 2017}}</ref> and recorded music for their second album while on tour.<ref name=\"fresca\"/>\n\nOn April 4, 2017, the group officially released the lead single from their second album, \"[[Hey DJ (CNCO song)|Hey DJ]]\", featuring Puerto Rican singer [[Yandel]]; they also released a solo pop version. On August 18, CNCO released a [[Reggaet\u00f3n Lento (Bailemos)#Little Mix remix|remixed version]] of \"Reggaet\u00f3n Lento\" featuring vocals from British girl group [[Little Mix]] as the second single from the record. On October 20, 2017, the group released the third single, \"[[Mamita (song)|Mamita]]\" from their second album. On March 3, 2018, they released the song, \"Mi Medicina,\" announcing the album's pre-order.<ref>{{cite web|title=CNCO tiene 'Mi medicina' y la tuya tambi\u00e9n|url=http://www.billboard.com.ar/noticia/4754/cnco-tiene-mi-medicina-y-la-tuya-tambin|date=March 2, 2018|language=Spanish|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard Argentina]]|accessdate=April 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407120116/http://www.billboard.com.ar/noticia/4754/cnco-tiene-mi-medicina-y-la-tuya-tambin|archive-date=April 7, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8220945/cnco-release-date-second-album|title=CNCO Reveal Release Date for Self-Titled Sophomore Album|work=Billboard|last=Fernandez|first=Suzette|date=February 26, 2018|accessdate=March 8, 2018}}</ref> It was followed by \"Bonita\" two weeks later, on March 16, and finally \"Fiesta en Mi Casa\", also arriving two weeks later, on March 30. The music videos accompanied the songs' releases.\n\nOn April 6, 2018, the boy band released their highly anticipated second self-titled album, ''[[CNCO (album)|CNCO]]''.<ref name=\"fresca\"/> It debuted at number one on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums|''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums]] and entered at number 33 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], succeeding their debut. The group released \"S\u00f3lo Yo\", along with its music video, to celebrate the album's release. The music video for the fifth single \"Se Vuelve Loca\" was made available on July 19, with a Spanglish version being released for digital download and streaming several hours later. It reached number one on the Latin Pop Songs Chart in October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8480828/cnco-se-vuelve-loca-latin-pop-songs-chart|title=CNCO's 'Se Vuelve Loca' Hits No. 1 on Latin Pop Songs Chart|last=Bustios|first=Pamela|date=October 19, 2018|website=Billboard|accessdate=November 8, 2018}}</ref> The band embarked on the CNCO World Tour, starting in Guatemala. They announced shows in the United States, thus becoming their first U.S. tour. The band released a collaboration with singer-songwriter [[Prince Royce]] on October 26, titled \"Llegaste T\u00fa\". On November 8, the group released a [[Hey DJ (CNCO song)#Meghan Trainor and Sean Paul remix|remix version]] of \"Hey DJ\", with American singer-songwriter [[Meghan Trainor]] and Jamaican artist [[Sean Paul]].\n\nOn May 16, 2018, CNCO signed a new management deal with Walter Kolm Entertainment, after being managed by Ricky Martin for nearly three years. Walter Kolm Entertainment has also signed other successful artists like [[Maluma (singer)|Maluma]], [[Wisin]], and [[Silvestre Dangond]].\n\n===2019-present: ''Que Quienes Somos''===\nThe band announced the single \"Pretend\", which was released on February 15, 2019. The song is their first official solo Spanglish release, and samples \"[[Rhythm of the Night (song)|Rhythm of the Night]]\" by [[DeBarge]].\n\nCNCO released the single \"De Cero\" on June 24 along with its music video. They performed a short version of \"Pretend\" at the [[2019 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards of 2019]], where they won the Choice Latin Artist and were nominated for Choice Group. Spanish singer-songwriter Abraham Mateo launched his song \"Me Vuelvo Loco\" in collaboration with the boys in July. The group revealed their first extended play, ''Que Qui\u00e9nes Somos'', in mid-August, along with its cover art. Its title references the line sung by Col\u00f3n at the end in most of their songs and also alludes as to who the boys are as they co-wrote the EP themselves. They released the first promotional single, titled \"Ya T\u00fa Sabes\" in the 23rd of the same month. It contains a sample of a song by Cuban salsa singer, [[Celia Cruz]] and features Latin Trap in its production. The second promotional song, named \"La Ley\", was made free on all digital platforms on September 27. Both songs were released with audios on YouTube. The EP was released on 11 October 2019 and includes seven tracks in total. They also released the single \"Pegao\" with [[Manuel Turizo]] on the same day with a music video. The EP ''Que Qui\u00e9nes Somos'' debuted at #1 on the Latin Pop Albums ''Billboard'' chart. The group collaborated with fellow boy band [[PRETTYMUCH]] on the song \"Me Necesita.\" CNCO performed \"Ya T\u00fa Sabes\" and also performed \"Me Vuelvo Loco\" alongside [[Abraham Mateo]] at the 2019 Latin American Music Awards and also won 2 awards that night. On November 7th the group was featured on the song \"[[Como As\u00ed]]\" by Argentinian singer [[Lali Esp\u00f3sito]], which will appear on her upcoming album. In the same month, CNCO announced a clothing campaign with [[Forever 21]].\n\n=== '''2020: Press Start Tour''' ===\nThe band announced their new tour \"Press Start\" on January 21, 2020. The tour will begin on May 30, 2020 at the [[Jos\u00e9 Miguel Agrelot Coliseum|Coliseo de Puerto Rico]] in San Juan, Puerto Rico. The first leg of the tour will consist of 11 cities. The first leg of the tour will end in Chicago, Illinois at the Rosemont Theater on June 21, 2020.\n<br />\n== Members ==\n\n=== Christopher V\u00e9lez ===\nChristopher Bryant V\u00e9lez Mu\u00f1oz was born on November 23, 1995 in [[New Jersey]]. He moved with his family to their home country, Ecuador when he was three years old. When he turned 18, V\u00e9lez returned to the U.S. in hopes of helping his family economically; he had several jobs, including shining shoes for a living. He originally wanted to go to school to study music but saw ''La Banda'' as a better opportunity. V\u00e9lez is also the oldest member in CNCO.<ref name=\"winners4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.axs.com/first-la-banda-winners-form-cnco-the-newest-latin-boy-band-72399|title=First 'La Banda' winners form CNCO: the newest Latin boy band|last=Irizarry|first=Doris|date=December 16, 2015|work=[[AXS TV|AXS]]|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Richard Camacho ===\nRichard Yashel Camacho Puello was born on January 22, 1997, in [[New York City]] and grew up in the [[Dominican Republic]]. His father is a musician and cameraman and his mother is a dancer, which is also a hobby for him. Camacho has been singing and dancing ever since he was just three years old, and the first song he has ever listened to was \"With You\" by [[Chris Brown]]. He has three other siblings; Yashua Camacho, who also took the lifestyle of singing and is a solo artist, Dairan Camacho and Yarliza Camacho. He has a daughter named Aaliyah Sofia Camacho, which he had with Instagram model, Yocelyn Alexander.<ref name=\"winners4\"/>\n\n=== Zabdiel De Jes\u00fas ===\nZabdiel De Jes\u00fas Col\u00f3n was born in [[Bayam\u00f3n, Puerto Rico]] on December 13, 1997. He developed an interest in singing at age twelve, singing with his church [[Hip hop music|hip-hop]] and [[Salsa music|salsa]] group, as well as dancing ballet at Ballet Concierto, a prestigious academy in Puerto Rico. As a young child, his father, a musician, showed him a love for the music that is now what keeps their family together. From a young age, De Jes\u00fas had the ability to play instruments that was incredible and that's where his love for music comes from. He has shown his skills at [[beatboxing]]. Interestingly, De Jes\u00fas' birthday is on the same day as the group's.<ref name=\"CNCO Music\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cncomusic.com/|title=CNCO Music|work=CNCOMusic.com|accessdate=August 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Joel Pimentel ===\nJoel Pimentel de Le\u00f3n was born in [[Victorville, California]] on February 28, 1999, but grew up in [[Hesperia, California|Hesperia]]. He has [[Mexican Americans|Mexican]] ancestry and was inspired by his late grandfather to pursue his music career. He was part of the drama club at [[Hesperia High School]], where he discovered his acting skills. In his spare time, Pimentel likes to play soccer, write songs and act. At one point during ''La Banda,'' Pimentel believed he would be eliminated because he couldn't speak or sing in Spanish very well as it was not his first language. However, his talent helped him become a member of CNCO.\n\n=== Erick Brian Col\u00f3n ===\nErick Brian Col\u00f3n Arista was born on January 3, 2001 in [[Havana]], [[Cuba]]. He moved to [[Tampa, Florida]] with his family at the age of 11 in 2012. There, Col\u00f3n played [[soccer]], danced and participated in musical activities at school. Col\u00f3n has a sister named Yanelis. He is the youngest member of the boyband and was in ''La Banda'' when he was just 14 years old.<ref name=\"winners4\" /><ref name=\" CNCO Music\" />\n\n== Reception ==\nGriselda Flores of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' said the band is \"taking the torch and leading a new boy band era\", like prior [[Latino (demonym)|Latino]] bands [[Magneto (band)|Magneto]], [[Menudo (band)|Menudo]], [[Uff!]], and [[:es:Salser\u00edn|Salser\u00edn]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7439041/magneto-cnco-menudo-latin-boy-band-poll|title=Magneto, CNCO or Menudo? Vote for Your All-Time Favorite Latin Boy Band!|last=Flores|first=Griselda|date=July 15, 2016|website=Billboard|accessdate=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{main|CNCO discography}}\n\n'''Studio albums'''\n* ''[[Primera Cita]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[CNCO (album)|CNCO]]'' (2018)\n\n'''Extended plays'''\n* ''Que Qui\u00e9nes Somos'' (2019)\n\n== Concert tours ==\n===Headlining===\n\n*2017: [[Primera Cita#M\u00e1s All\u00e1 Tour|M\u00e1s All\u00e1 Tour]]<ref name=\"finalists\" /><ref name=\"tour dates\" />\n*2018-2019: [[CNCO (album)#CNCO World Tour|CNCO World Tour]]\n* 2020: Press Start Tour<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://substreammagazine.com/2020/01/cnco-press-start-tour-2020/|title=CNCO announce first leg of 2020 \"Press Start\" tour|last=White|first=Logan|date=2020-01-22|website=Substream Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref>\n\n===As opening act===\n* 2016: [[One World Tour (Ricky Martin)|Ricky Martin's One World Tour]]<ref name=\"HardRock\"/><ref name=\"martintour\"/>\n*2017: [[Ariana Grande]] \u2013 [[Dangerous Woman Tour]]\n* 2017: [[Enrique Iglesias And Pitbull Tour]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Flores|first=Griselda|title=Enrique Iglesias, Pitbull & CNCO Kick Off Tour With Sold-Out Concert in Chicago|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7817594/pitbull-enrique-iglesias-cnco-chicago-concert-recap|date=June 4, 2017|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n[[File:CNCO Lo Nuestro 1.jpg|thumb|right|CNCO receiving award at [[Lo Nuestro Awards]] 2017, with Ricky Martin]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category\n!Nominated work\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"10\" |2016\n|